{"title_page": "Tabs of the United States Army", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{US Army tabs|state = uncollapsed}}\n{{Listen\n| image    = [[File:Video Camera Icon.png|50px]]\n| help     = no\n| filename = Earn the Tab-Intro.ogv\n| title    = Earning the Tab\n| description = Official Army video introducing and describing tabs in the U.S. Army\n| pos      = right\n}}\nIn the [[United States Army]], '''\"tabs\"''' are small cloth and/or metal arches displaying a word or words signifying a special skill that are worn on U.S. Army uniforms. On the [[Army Combat Uniform]], the tabs are worn above a unit's [[Shoulder Sleeve Insignia (United States Army)|shoulder patch]] and are used to identify a unit's or a soldier's special skill(s) or are worn on shoulder patches as part of a unit's unique heritage. Individual tabs are also worn as small metal arches above or below [[Awards and decorations of the United States Army|medals or ribbons]] on the [[Army Service Uniform]].\n\nTabs are valued uniquely in the U.S. Army because images rather than words are traditionally used for the [[symbol]]ism of the shoulder patch worn to identify a soldier's unit. It is only to identify an individual soldier's or a whole unit's special skill that an additional shoulder patch is worn that uses words rather than images to symbolize this skill. For example, while any member of a special forces unit will wear the unit identifying patch that includes an arrowhead, sword, lightning, and Airborne Tab, only soldiers who have completed special forces training will have been awarded and wear an additional tab containing the words \"SPECIAL FORCES\" (i.e. the Special Forces Tab).\n\nSome tabs are awarded to recognize an individual soldier's combat related skills or marksmanship and are worn by a soldier permanently. These tabs are also considered [[Badges of the United States Army|special skill badges]] and have metal equivalents that are worn on the soldier's chest if their uniform does not have a place for shoulder patches (e.g. the Army Service Uniform). Other tabs recognize a whole unit's special skill and are considered to be part of a specific unit's shoulder sleeve patch and are worn by a soldier only while they belong to that unit.<ref>[http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/Tab/Tabs.htm Pentagon.mil]</ref> The Jungle Expert Tab is unique in that while it is awarded to recognize an individual soldier's skill, it is only worn by soldiers while they belong to certain units.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmedals.com/detail.aspx?ID=5717|title=USmedals.com|publisher=|accessdate=3 March 2018}}</ref> Similarly, tabs awarded at the state level by the U.S. Army National Guard can only be worn by soldiers while they are on state-level orders.\n\n==Individual tabs==\nThere are currently four permanent individual skill/marksmanship tabs authorized for wear by the U.S. Army. In order of precedence, they are the [[Special Forces Tab]], the [[Ranger Tab]], the [[Sapper Tab]], and the [[President's Hundred Tab]]. Only three skill tabs may be worn at one time.<ref name=\"P670-1\">[http://www.apd.army.mil/pdffiles/p670_1.pdf U.S. Army Pamphlet 670\u20131: Uniform and Insignia, Guide to the Wear and Appearance of Army Uniforms and Insignia] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506235717/http://www.apd.army.mil/pdffiles/p670_1.pdf |date=6 May 2014 }}, Department of the Army, dated 31 March 2014, last accessed 7 March 2015</ref> A soldier wearing three skill tabs is said to have achieved the \"tower of power\" or a \"triple canopy\" in military slang.\n\n===Special Forces===\n[[File:SpecialForcesTabMetal.jpg|170px|thumb|Special Forces Tab]]\nThe [[Special Forces Tab]] is a service school qualification tab of the [[United States Army]], awarded to any soldier completing either the [[Special Forces Qualification Course]], or the Special Forces Detachment Officer Qualification Course. Soldiers who are awarded the Special Forces Tab are authorized to wear it for the remainder of their military careers, even when not serving in a [[United States Army Special Forces|Special Forces]] command. The Special Forces Tab can be revoked by the Chain of Command for significant violations of conduct considered contrary to the high standards expected of a Special Forces soldier (for example, DUI or other forms of misconduct).\n\nThe Special Forces Tab was created in 1983 and is an embroidered quadrant patch worn on the upper left sleeve of a military uniform. The cloth tab is {{convert|3+7/4|in|cm}} wide and is teal blue with yellow embroidered letters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qmmuseum.lee.army.mil/airborne/sf_tab.htm|title=Special Forces Tab|website=www.qmmuseum.lee.army.mil|accessdate=3 March 2018}}</ref><ref>Army Regulation 600-8-22, Section 8-49.</ref>\n\n===Ranger===\n[[File:Ranger Tab.svg|150px|thumb|Ranger Tab]]\nThe Ranger Tab is a qualification tab authorized upon completion of the [[Ranger School|U.S. Army's Ranger School]] by a member of the U.S. military, civilian personnel, or non-U.S. military personnel. The Ranger Tab was approved by the Chief of Staff, Army, on 30 October 1950. The Ranger Tab can be revoked IAW AR 600-8-22, Section 1-31, para. 13.\n\nThe full color tab is worn {{convert|1/2|in|cm}} below the shoulder seam on the left sleeve of the Army green coat. The subdued tab is worn {{convert|1/2|in|cm}} below the shoulder seam on the left sleeve of utility uniforms, field jackets and the desert battle dress uniform (DBDU). The full color tab is {{convert|2+3/8|in|cm}} long, {{convert|11/16|in|cm}} wide, with a {{convert|1/8|in|cm}} yellow border and the word \"RANGER\" inscribed in yellow letters {{convert|5/16|in|cm}} high. The subdued tab is identical, except the background is olive drab and the word \"RANGER\" is in black letters.<ref>[http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/tab/RangerTab.htm Pentagon.mil]</ref>\n\n===Sapper===\n[[File:SapperFullColorTab.jpg|150px|thumb|Sapper Tab]]\nThe Sapper Tab is a qualification tab which is authorized for graduates of the [[Sapper School|U.S. Army's Sapper School]]. The Sapper Tab was approved by the Chief of Staff, Army, on 28 June 2004. The Sapper tab can be revoked by the Engineer Commanding Officer of Ft. Leonard Wood, MO for misconduct, or not upholding the standard as an Engineer. Any requests will be processed through USASC.<ref>[http://www.wood.army.mil/sapper/document_frames/Pamphlet.doc Sapper leader course pamphlet] section III, US Army</ref><ref>[http://www.apd.army.mil/jw2/xmldemo/r670_1/main.asp#p029-1 Wear and Appearance of Army Uniforms and Insignia] US Army</ref>\n\nThe full color tab is worn {{convert|1/2|in|cm}} below the shoulder seam on the left sleeve of the Army green coat. The subdued tab is worn {{convert|1/2|in|cm}} below the shoulder seam on the left sleeve of utility uniforms, field jackets and the desert battle dress uniform (DBDU). The full color tab is {{convert|2+3/8|in|cm}} long, {{convert|11/16|in|cm}} wide, with a {{convert|1/8|in|cm}} red border and the word \"SAPPER\" inscribed in white letters {{convert|5/16|in|cm}} high. The woodland subdued tab is identical, except the background is olive drab and the word \"SAPPER\" is in black letters and the desert subdued tab has a khaki background with the word \"SAPPER\" in spice brown letters.<ref>[http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/tab/SapperTab.htm Pentagon.mil]</ref>\n\n===President's Hundred===\n[[File:Presidents 100 Metal Tab.jpg|210px|thumb|President's Hundred Tab]]\nThe [[President's Hundred Tab]] is a marksmanship tab which is authorized for soldiers who qualify among the top 100 scoring competitors in the President's Match held annually at the National Rifle Matches at Camp Perry, Ohio. This is a permanent award which will stay with the individual; there is no annual requirement to maintain the President's Hundred Tab. Most competitors will compete each year to ensure that less qualified individuals do not receive the tab.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uscg.mil/directives/cim/1000-1999/CIM_1020_6F.pdf|title=USCG.mil|publisher=|accessdate=3 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 May 1958, The National Rifle Association requested the Deputy Chief of Staff for Personnel's approval of a tab for presentation to each member of the \"President's Hundred.\" NRA's plan was to award the cloth tab together with a metal tab during the 1958 National Matches. The cloth tab was of high level interest and approved for wear on the uniform on 3 March 1958.<ref name=\"Short History\">[http://thecmp.org/wp-content/uploads/PresidentsMatchHistory1.pdf A Short History of the President's Match and the President's Hundred], by Hap Rocketto, dated 19 March 8, last accessed 26 November 2017</ref>\n\nA full-color embroidered tab of yellow {{convert|4+1/4|in|cm}} long and {{convert|5/8|in|cm}} high, with the word \"President's Hundred\" centered in {{convert|1/4|in|cm}} high green letters. The metal replica is {{convert|2|in|cm}} wide.<ref>[http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/tab/PresidentsHundredTab.htm Pentagon.mil]</ref>\n\n===Governor's X (National Guard)===\n[[File:Governors Twenty Tab-ABU.png|190px|thumb|Governor's Twenty Tab]]\nThe '''[[Marksmanship badges (United States)|Governor's Twenty Tab]]''' is a [[National Guard of the United States|state-level National Guard]] award, created in 1968, that is awarded to the top 20 shooters in a state. However, award criteria vary from state-to-state. For example, within the [[Texas Military Forces]], only eight guardsmen are presented this award for rifle, eight for pistol, two for sniper, and two for machine gun each year. Texas guardsmen compete against other Texas guardsman who have already received the award; thus, there may be one or two new recipients of this award each year. As of July 2014, 14 states have authorized the awarding of the Governor's Twenty Tab.<ref>[http://www.txmarks.org/combatprogram/governors20.htm Texas National Guard Marksmanship Program, Governor's Twenty], Texas National Guard, updated 4 Aug 11, last accessed 13 Nov 11</ref><ref>[http://www.txsg.state.tx.us/txsg-team-wins-first-place-in-2009-texas-adjutant-general%E2%80%99s-combat-pistol-sustainment-exercise-competition.aspx TXSG Team Wins First Place In 2009 Texas Adjutant General\u2019s Combat Pistol Sustainment Exercise Competition], Texas State Guard, by Maj. J. Michael Spraggins, dated 7 May 7, last accessed 13 Nov 11</ref><ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/texasmilitaryforces/11932768054/in/set-72157639729854336 Governor's 20 Sniper Competition 2014], Texas Military Forces, dated 12 January 2014, last accessed 19 January 2014</ref><ref>[http://vaguard.dodlive.mil/2014/08/07/5784/ Earning the Governor\u2019s Twenty Tab], By CPT Andrew J. Czaplicki, dated 7 August 2014, last accessed 10 January 2015</ref>\n\n[[File:Governors Twelve Tab-ABU.png|200px|thumb|Governor's Twelve/Dozen Tab]]\nIn the [[Missouri National Guard]] and [[Arizona National Guard]], the top twelve guardsman selected to represent their state at the [[Winston P. Wilson]] Rifle and Pistol Championships are awarded the '''Governor's Twelve Tab''', for Missouri guardsman, or the '''Governor's Dozen Tab''', for Arizona guardsman. These tabs are worn on the upper-left sleeve of the Army Combat Uniform below individual tabs and above unit and honor guard tabs. The Missouri National Guard also award a [[Awards and decorations of the National Guard#Missouri|Governor's Twelve Ribbon]] that accompanies the tab which is worn on dress uniforms; any guardsman who earns the award more than once wear [[Marksmanship Device|Hawthorn Cluster Devices]] on top of the ribbon.<ref name=\"MO Guard\">[http://www.moguard.com/12-14-10-tabs-and-badges-a-measure-of-marksmanship.html Tabs and Badges a Measure of Marksmanship] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140518224313/http://www.moguard.com/12-14-10-tabs-and-badges-a-measure-of-marksmanship.html |date=18 May 2014 }}, Missouri National Guard, dated 14 December 2010, last accessed 18 May 2014</ref><ref>[http://www.frontiernet.net/~ericbush/US/NG/Ng_attac.htm National Guard Devices], by Eric Bush, last accessed 18 May 2014</ref><ref>[https://www.army.mil/article/166150/Arizona_National_Guard_s_top_marksmen_awarded_Governor_s_Dozen Arizona National Guard's top marksmen awarded Governor's Dozen], Army.mil, by SGT Wesley Parrell, dated 15 April 2016, last accessed 5 February 2017</ref>\n\n[[File:Governors X Tab-ABU.png|165px|thumb|Governor's Ten Tab]]\nIn the [[Iowa National Guard]], the top ten rifle and/or pistol shooters from the state's Army and Air Force guard units, as well as local Army Reserve units, that compete at the Iowa Governor's 10 Shooting Competition are awarded the '''Governor's Ten Tab.''' Prior to 2008, the Governor's Ten Tab was awarded to the top five pistol shooters and top five rifle shooters. Today, the rifle and pistol scores are combined so only the best 10 overall shooters earn the tab.<ref>[https://www.dvidshub.net/news/66840/top-iowa-marksmen-train-fellow-red-bulls-afghans-torkham-gate#.VPH2XfnF8Zl Top Iowa marksmen train fellow Red Bulls, Afghans at Torkham Gate], Defense Video and Imagery Distribution System, by Staff Sgt Ryan Matson, dated 11 March 2011, last accessed 28 February 2015</ref>\n\nBecause these awards are state-level awards, soldiers and airmen in the National Guard under federal status ([[Title 10 of the United States Code|Title 10 of the U.S. Code]]) are not authorized to wear these awards until they return to [[Title 32 of the United States Code|Title 32 status]].<ref name=\"P670-1\"/><ref name=\"MO Guard\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Jungle (US Army Pacific)===\n{{multiple image\n|align    = right\n|direction= vertical\n|width1   = 185\n|image1   = Jungle Expert Tab.jpg\n|caption1 = Original Jungle Expert Tab\n|width2   = 150\n|image2   = Jungle Tab.svg\n|caption2 = Current Jungle Tab\n}}\n{{Stack|[[File:Jungle Expert Logo.png|thumb|right|175px|Former Jungle Expert Patch]]}}\nThe Jungle Expert Patch was often worn by graduates of the [[Jungle Operations Training Center]] (JOTC) at [[Fort Sherman]] until the school became inactive in 1999. The patch was authorized for wear by soldiers assigned to [[U.S. Army South]] who graduate from JOTC but the patch was never recognized Army-wide. In 2014, the JOTC was reopened in Hawaii and the Jungle Expert Patch was revitalized as a tab which is authorized for wear by soldiers who complete the course and are assigned to the [[U.S. Army Pacific]] [[area of responsibility]]. However the revitalized tab now simply reads 'Jungle' instead of 'Jungle Expert'.<ref>[http://www.benning.army.mil/infantry/magazine/issues/2014/Jan-Mar/Eifler.html Welcome (Back) to the Jungle], Infantry Online, Benning.armuy.mil, by COL Brian S. Eifler, dated Jan-Mar 2014 edition, last accessed 16 July 2016</ref><ref>[https://www.army.mil/article/210898/tamc_combat_medic_named_honor_grad_at_25id_jungle_school TAMC combat medic named honor grad at 25ID 'Jungle School'], www.army.mil, by Leanne Thomas, dated 7 September 2018, last accessed 23 February 2020</ref><ref>[https://www.army.mil/article/231985/not_for_the_faint_hearted_triplers_chief_judge_advocate_graduates_executive_jungle_school Not for the faint hearted: Tripler's Chief Judge Advocate graduates executive jungle school], www.army.mil, by SGT Natalie Kintz,, dated 23 January 2020, 23 February 2020</ref>  Other graduates of the course receive the tab as a souvenir.\n\n===Arctic (US Army Alaska)===\n[[File:U.S. Army Arctic Tab.png|thumb|right|140px|USARAK's Arctic Tab]]\nThe Arctic Tab is an individual skill tab earned by those who graduate from the Cold Weather Orientation Course or Cold Weather Leadership Course held at the [[Northern Warfare Training Center]].<ref>[https://www.army.mil/article/139127/Are_you_Arctic_Tough_/ Are you Arctic Tough?], www.army.mil, dated 26 November 2014, last accessed 7 May 2016</ref> The tab is authorized by [[United States Army Alaska|U.S. Army Alaska]] (USARAK) for wear on combat uniforms above the SSI of units assigned to USARAK while operating in the [[Alaska|State of Alaska]].<ref>[http://www.wainwright.army.mil/nwtc/Images/Website/NCOJournal.pdf Training for the Colld] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314104303/http://www.wainwright.army.mil/nwtc/Images/Website/NCOJournal.pdf |date=14 March 2016 }}; NCO Journal, volume 21, number 3, dated March 2012; page 26 (pdf page 8); last accessed 7 May 2016</ref>\n\n==Unit tabs==\nA [[shoulder sleeve insignia]] (SSI) is an embroidered patch worn on some uniforms of the United States Army that identifies the wearer's major formation. Unit tabs are an integral part of the SSI and are never worn separately. Soldiers are only authorized to wear the tab while assigned to the organization that prescribes wearing the SSI with the tab.\n\n===Airborne===\n{{multiple image\n|footer = Airborne Tabs\n|align  = right\n|width  = 150\n|image1 = AirborneYellowTab.gif\n|image2 = AirborneBlueandWhiteTab.jpg\n|image3 = Airborne Red Tab.jpg\n}}\nThe Airborne Tab is a part of the SSI of certain [[Airborne forces|airborne]] and [[air assault]] units. Airborne and air assault forces are [[military]] units, usually [[light infantry]], set up to be moved by [[aircraft]] and dropped into battle. Thus, they can be placed behind enemy lines and have an ability to deploy almost anywhere with little warning. The tab is worn immediately above and touching the SSI. The tabs are {{convert|2+1/2|in|cm}} long and {{convert|11/16|in|cm}} wide. The letters are {{convert|5/16|in|cm}} high.<ref>[http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/Catalog/Heraldry.aspx?HeraldryId=16088&CategoryId=20&grp=2&menu=Uniformed%20Services&ps=24&p=0 The U.S. Army Institute of Heraldry, Tabs, Airborne Tabs], tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil, last accessed 26 November 2017</ref>\n\n===Mountain===\n[[File:MTN-TAB.png|150px|thumb|Mountain Tab]]\nThe Mountain Tab is a part of the SSI of the [[10th Mountain Division]], the [[Northern Warfare Training Center]], and the [[Army National Guard]] Regional Training Institute's [[Cadre (military)|cadre]] assigned to the [[Army Mountain Warfare School]].  The 10th Mountain Division retains the Mountain Tab for historical purposes but is actually organized as a light infantry division.  For a period of time, the [[86th Infantry Brigade Combat Team|86th Infantry Brigade Combat Team (Mountain)]] was the only other unit whose SSI was authorized to incorporate the Mountain Tab, due to the nature of that [[Vermont Army National Guard]] brigade's training.  Under the [[Reorganization plan of United States Army#.22Associated units.22 training program|US Army's \"associated units\" program]], the 86th IBCT is now aligned under the 10th Mountain Division and wear that historic division's SSI.\n\nAlthough they do not wear the Mountain Tab, mountain warfare training is a basic component of the US Army's [[Ranger School]] and each US Army [[Special Forces (United States Army)|Special Forces Group]] maintain detachments that specialize in mountain warfare.\n\n===Advisor===\n[[File:US Army 1st SFAB SSI tab.png|150px|thumb|SFAB Tab]]\nOne of the US Army's newest units, the [[Security Force Assistance Brigade]]s (SFABs), was authorized a unit SSI that incorporates a unique tab that was initially embroidered with the words \"ADVISE - ASSIST.\" Shortly after the SFAB's SSI was authorized for wear, the tab was changed to read \"COMBAT ADVISOR\".<ref name=\"1st SFAB SSI\">[https://www.facebook.com/1SFAB/photos/a.1768924863407411.1073741827.1767763830190181/1802696690030228/?type=3&theater The 1st Security Force Assistance Brigade official Facebook page, New Shoulder Sleeve Insignia], dated 1 November 2017, last accessed 3 November 2017</ref> The SFAB SSI was changed again sometime before the 1st SFAB's official activation ceremony and their unit tab now reads simply \"ADVISOR\".<ref name=\"1st SFAB Activation Ceremony\">[https://www.army.mil/article/200244/1st_sfab_hosts_activation_ceremony_heraldry_announced 1st SFAB hosts activation ceremony; Heraldry announced], Army.mil, dated 8 February 2018, last accessed 2 March 2018</ref>\n\n===Honor Guard===\n{{multiple image\n|footer = Honor Guard Tabs\n|align  = right\n|width  = 180\n|image1 = HonorGuardTab1Bn3InfRegtTab.jpg\n|alt1   = Honor Guard Tab of the 3rd Inf Reg\n|caption1 = Honor Guard Tab of the 3rd Infantry Regiment\n|image2 = Honor Guard Blue on White Tab.jpg\n|alt2   = Honor Guard Tab for select units\n|caption2 = Honor Guard Tab for select units\n|image3 = ARNG Honor Guard Tab.png\n|alt3  = ARNG Honor Guard Tab\n|caption3 = Army National Guard Honor Guard Tab for select units\n}}\nThe Honor Guard Tab is a part of the SSI of the [[3d US Infantry Regiment (The Old Guard)|3rd U.S. Infantry Regiment (The Old Guard)]] and other selected units with ceremonial duties. The tab had been worn by the Honor Guard Company of the 1st Battle Group, 3d Infantry (The Old Guard) since early 1950. It was officially approved for wear by the Deputy Chief of Staff for Personnel (DCSPER) on 14 October 1959. The 3rd Infantry's tab is ultramarine blue {{convert|3+7/8|in|cm}} long and {{convert|11/16|in|cm}} high, the designation \"HONOR GUARD\" in white letters {{convert|5/16|in|cm}} high. The subdued tab is identical, except the background is olive drab and the letters are black.<ref>[http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/Catalog/Heraldry.aspx?HeraldryId=16089&CategoryId=20&grp=2&menu=Uniformed%20Services&ps=24&p=0 Honor Guard Tab for 1st Battalion, 3rd Infantry Regiment], U.S. Army Institute of Heraldry, last accessed 1 February 2015</ref>\n\nOn 16 March 1965, the DCSPER approved a white tab with ultramarine blue lettering for wear by select Honor Guard units throughout the U.S. Army. Proposed designs were submitted on 26 March 1965 and the color reversed version of The Old Guard's tab was approved on 19 April 1965. A subdued tab is also authorized.<ref>[http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/Catalog/Heraldry.aspx?HeraldryId=16090&CategoryId=20&grp=2&menu=Uniformed%20Services&ps=24&p=0 Honor Guard Tab for Selected Units], U.S. Army Institute of Heraldry, last accessed 1 February 2015</ref> Additionally, there are other select Army and Army National Guard units that have their own distinctive Honor Guard Tabs that are not defined in general Army uniform regulations, such as the [[United Nations Command]] Honor Guard that wear a red (or scarlet) tab with white letters on the left shoulder of their service dress uniform.<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/UNCHG/ UNC Honor Guard (Official) Facebook page], last accessed 10 July 2016</ref>\n\nOn 31 December 2012, the DCSPER approved another Honor Guard Tab for wear by select Army National Guard units. The new tab is an ultramarine blue embroidered tab with the inscription \"ARNG HONOR GUARD\" in gold {{convert|5/16|in|cm}} letters, edged with a {{convert|1/8|in|cm}} gold border.<ref>[http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/Catalog/Heraldry.aspx?HeraldryId=17675&CategoryId=20&grp=2&menu=Uniformed%20Services&ps=24&p=0 Army National Guard Honor Guard Tab], U.S. Army Institute of Heraldry, last accessed 1 February 2015</ref>\n\n===Band===\n{{multiple image\n|footer = Examples of some select unit's Army Band Tabs\n|align  = right\n|width  = 180\n|image1 = TRADOC Band Tab.png\n|caption1 = [[United States Army Training and Doctrine Command|US Army Training and Doctrine Command]] Band Tab<ref>[http://www.facebook.com/TRADOCBand?fref=ts U.S. Army Training and Doctrine Command Band Facebook page], last accessed 31 May 2017</ref>\n|image2 = US Army Reserve 100th Army Band Tab.png\n|caption2 = 100th Army Band Tab of the [[United States Army Reserve|US Army Reserve]]'s [[81st Infantry Division (United States)|81st Regional Support Command]]<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/100thArmyBand/ 100th Army Band Facebook page], last accessed 31 May 2017</ref>\n|image3 = 122nd Army Band Tab.png\n|caption3 = 122nd Army Band Tab of the [[Ohio Army National Guard]]'s [[371st Sustainment Brigade (United States)|371st Sustainment Brigade]]<ref>[http://www.122ndarmyband.com/download/122nd_Army_Band_Tab_371st_Sustainment_Brigade_Patch.jpg 371st Sustainment Brigade Shoulder Sleeve Insignia with 122nd Army Band Tab], 122nd Army Band Homepage, last accessed 31 May 2017</ref>\n}}\nSimilar to the Honor Guard Tab for select units, the Band Tab is worn by an Army band within a given unit.<ref name=\"TIOH Band\">[http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/Catalog/HeraldryList.aspx?CategoryId=211&grp=2&menu=Uniformed%20Services Distinctive Unit Insignia, Shoulder Sleeve Insignia, and Coat of Arms / Bands /], [[United States Army Institute of Heraldry]] (TIOH), last accessed 31 May 2017</ref> The exception to this is the [[United States Army Field Band|U.S. Army Field Band]] Tab which is an integral part of that unit's SSI,<ref>[http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/Catalog/HeraldryMulti.aspx?CategoryId=2967&grp=2&menu=Uniformed%20Services U.S. Army Field Band, Shoulder Sleeve Insignia], TIOH, last accessed 31 May 2017</ref> just like the Mountain Tab worn by the 10th Mountain Division. Each Army unit that has a band can have its own unique Band Tab, designed by the [[U.S. Army Institute of Heraldry]], and can only be worn with that unit's SSI.<ref name=\"TIOH Band\"/> Once a band member leaves the band to join another element of the same unit, they can no longer wear the Band Tab but continue to wear their unit's SSI. Subdued versions of each unit's Band Tab is authorized for wear with their unit's subdued SSI.<ref>[https://www.army.mil/article/130069/TRADOC_hosts_Twilight_Tattoo TRADOC hosts Twilight Tattoo (Example of U.S. Army Band Tab worn above the U.S. Army Military District of Washington / Fort McNair Shoulder Sleeve Insignia)], Army.mil, by Staff Sgt. Jennifer C. Johnson (JFHQ-NCR/MDW Public Affairs), dated 17 July 2014, last accessed 31 May 2017</ref>\n\n===Combined Division===\n[[File:US Army Combined Division Tab.png|thumb|right|180px|2nd ID's combined HQ tab]]\nOn 29 December 2015, the U.S. Army approved the wear of a black tab by soldiers assigned to Headquarters, [[2nd Infantry Division (United States)|2nd Infantry Division]] (ID). This black tab, worn immediately above the 2nd ID's SSI, is embroidered with white English and Korean letters spelling out the words \"Combined Division.\"<ref name=\"TIOH 2nd ID\">[http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/Catalog/Heraldry.aspx?HeraldryId=17971&CategoryId=20&grp=2&menu=Uniformed%20Services&ps=24&p=0 Combined Division Tab], The U.S. Army's Institute of Heraldry, dated 29 December 2015, last accessed 16 April 2016</ref> The tab is used to signify the joint nature of the new combined headquarters made up of units from the U.S. Army's 2nd ID<ref name=\"Stars & Strips\">[http://www.stripes.com/news/pacific/korea/us-south-korea-activate-1st-ever-combined-division-1.350251 US, South Korea activate 1st-ever combined division], Stars and Stripes, by Ashley Rowland, dated 3 June 2015, last accessed 16 April 2016</ref> and the [[Republic of Korea Army]]'s (ROKA) [[8th Infantry Division (South Korea)|8th ID]],<ref name=\"Stars & Strips\"/><ref name=\"ROKA OB for 16th Bde\">[http://www.army.mil/article/148361/ROKA_16th_Brigade_staff_visits_1st_ABCT/ ROKA 16th Brigade staff visits 1st ABCT], U.S. Army Homepage, by CPL SeoWon Lee, dated 12 May 2015, last accessed 16 April 2016</ref> established on 3 June 2015.<ref name=\"Stars & Strips\"/> The tab may only be worn by U.S. Army 2nd ID and ROKA 8th ID headquarters soldiers while serving within the geographical boundaries and territorial waters of the [[Republic of Korea]].<ref name=\"TIOH 2nd ID\"/>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Unofficial, obsolete, and other==\nSeveral tabs are widely worn unofficially by members of the U.S. Army. Often these tabs were worn on the underside of pocket flaps so as not to violate uniform regulations. Such tabs also appear on stickers, shirts, hats, etc. that soldiers would wear with civilian attire. These include tabs containing the words \"SNIPER\", \"AIR ASSAULT\", \"[[Artillery observer|FISTER]]\", \"SCOUT\", and \"RECON\" or \"[[Recondo|RECONDO]].\" The \"SAPPER\" tab was one of these unofficial tabs until 2004 when it became an official special skill badge/tab of the U.S. Army.\n\n===Recondo===\n{{multiple image\n|align    = right\n|width1   = 145\n|image1   = Recondo.jpg\n|caption1 = Recondo Tab\n|width2   = 145\n|image2   = US Army ROTC Recondo Badge.png\n|caption2 = ROTC Recondo Badge\n}}\n[[Recondo]] was a [[Vietnam War]]-era title meant to designate Soldiers of the wider US Army trained in Ranger tactics but without having been sent to Ranger school. The title \"Recondo\" stood for \"Reconnaissance Commando\". The standard Recondo insignia was a downward-pointing arrowhead with \"RECONDO\" printed above. The Recondo patch was standardly worn on each graduate's right breast pocket. Recondo was also sometimes worn in the style of the more traditional shoulder tab.\n\nIn designing the unit patch for the [[Security Force Assistance Brigade]] stood up in 2018, the US Army took inspiration from the classic Recondo arrowhead design. The original unit patch design was eventually softened to less directly replicate the Recondo arrowhead patch after complaints from the US Army special forces community.<ref>{{cite web |title=Beret for Soldiers of 1st SFAB \u2013 Concern in SF Community |url=https://sof.news/sfa/sfab-beret/}}</ref> The SFAB unit patches also introduced the new \"ADVISOR\" unit level tab to the Army uniform.\n\nThe US Army ROTC still issues a Recondo Badge to cadets who successfully complete Recondo training at the Leader Development and Assessment Course.\n\n===Pershing===\n[[File:US Army Pershing Tab of the Former 56th Field Artillery Command.png|right|thumb|160px|Pershing Tab]]\nThe Pershing Tab was worn as part of the shoulder sleeve insignia (SSI) for units supporting the [[Pershing missile]] system. From 1970 to 1971 the [[56th Artillery Brigade]] wore the SSI of the Seventh Army with the Pershing tab. In 1971 the 56th FA received their own SSI that included the Pershing tab, which continued through redesignation as the 56th Field Artillery Command in 1986. The [[3rd Battalion, 9th Field Artillery Regiment]] wore the Pershing tab with the SSI of [[III Corps (United States)|III Corps]] from 1971 to 1981, then with that of the [[214th Field Artillery Brigade]] when it had a SSI created in 1981. The Pershing tab was discontinued with the deactivation of units following the elimination of the [[Pershing missile]] system in 1991.<ref>{{cite web |title=56th Field Artillery Command: Shoulder Sleeve Insignia; Distinctive Unit Insignia |work=[[United States Army Institute of Heraldry]] |url=http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/Catalog/HeraldryMulti.aspx?CategoryId=3448&grp=2&menu=Uniformed%20Services}}</ref>\n\n===Air Assault===\n[[File:US Army 11th Air Assault Tab-Historical.png|160px|thumb|SSI tab of the former 11th Air Assault Division]]\nIn 1963, the [[11th Airborne Division (United States)#Reactivation (11th Air Assault Division) and inactivation|11th Air Assault Division (Test)]] was established\u2014formed from reactivated elements of the [[11th Airborne Division (United States)|11th Airborne Division]]\u2014to explore the theory and practicality of [[air assault|helicopter assault tactics]], and was inactivated two years later when testing was completed and the [[1st Cavalry Division (United States)|1st Cavalry Division (Airmobile)]] was formed. Although this test unit wore the shoulder sleeve insignia of the 11th Airborne Division, they replaced their Airborne Tab with a unique Air Assault Tab, believed to be the first and last approved Air Assault Tab in the U.S. Army.\n\n===Army Air Forces' Command Identification===\n[[File:US Army Air Forces Command Tab-Training Command.png|180px|thumb|Example: The AAF Training Command SSI tab]]\nWith the expansion of the [[United States Army Air Forces|U.S. Army Air Forces]] (AAF) in [[World War II]], the [[:File:US Army Air Corps Hap Arnold Wings.svg|AAF SSI]] became one of the most widely worn shoulder insignias of the war.<ref name=\"AAF Tabs\">[http://www.angelfire.com/md2/patches/airforcearcs.html United States Army, Second World War, Air Force Command Arcs], angelfire.com, by Dr. Howard G. Lanham, last accessed 3 April 2020</ref>  Given the AAF SSI did not allow someone to determine which AAF command the wearer belonged, on 28 July 1945 the U.S. Army approved the use of Command Identification Tabs\u2014also known as an arc\u2014to help identify an AAF solder's command.<ref name=\"AAF Tabs\"/><ref name=\"Weatherman History\">[https://media.defense.gov/2015/Sep/11/2001329838/-1/-1/0/AFD-150911-027.pdf Air Force Weather, Our Heritage 1937 to 2012], prepared by TSgt C. A. Ravenstein (Historical Division, AW3DI, Hq AWS), dated 22 January 2012, last accessed 3 April 2020</ref><ref name=\"AAF Arcs\">[http://www.usmilitariaforum.com/forums/index.php?/topic/233240-ww2post-ww2-us-army-aaf-command-tabsarcs/ WW2/Post WW2 US Army AAF Command Tabs/Arcs], usmilitariaforum.com, last accessed 3 April 2020</ref>  These Command Identification Tabs were worn above the AAF SSI as an arc that followed the curvature of the SSI and was embroidered with the name of the AAF command in the same blue and gold colors as the SSI.<ref name=\"AAF Tabs\"/><ref name=\"Weatherman History\"/><ref name=\"AAF Arcs\"/>  The use of these Command Identification Tabs continued until the introduction of the [[United States Air Force|U.S. Air Force]] blue uniform.<ref name=\"Weatherman History\"/>\n\n===Ranger Challenge (ROTC)===\n[[File:Ranger challenge.png|thumb|160px|'''Ranger Challenge Tab''']]\nThe '''Ranger Challenge Tab''' is the only [[United States Department of the Army]] individual qualification tab awarded exclusively to [[Reserve Officers' Training Corps]] cadets. This award is presented annually to cadets who compete in regional ROTC [[Army Reserve Officers' Training Corps#Activities and clubs|Ranger Challenge competitions]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ranger Challenge Tab]]\n* [[Badges of the United States Army]]\n* [[Uniforms of the United States Army]]\n* [[United States military beret flash]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n[https://armypubs.army.mil/ProductMaps/PubForm/Details.aspx?PUB_ID=1003738] \n\n[http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/Tab/SapperTab.htm Pentagon Institute of Heraldry's Sapper Tab Page]\n* [http://usmilitary.about.com/od/army/a/sappertab.htm About.com Sapper Tab Article]\n\n{{US Army badges}}\n{{Military badges of the United States}}\n{{US Army uniforms}}\n{{Pershing missile}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tabs Of The United States Army}}\n[[Category:Awards and decorations of the United States Army]]\n[[Category:United States military badges]]\n[[Category:United States Army uniforms]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Pershing missile]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{US Army tabs|state = uncollapsed}}\n{{Listen\n| image    = [[File:Video Camera Icon.png|50px]]\n| help     = no\n| filename = Earn the Tab-Intro.ogv\n| title    = Earning the Tab\n| description = Official Army video introducing and describing tabs in the U.S. Army\n| pos      = right\n}}\nIn the [[United States Army]], '''\"tabs\"''' are small cloth and/or metal arches displaying a word or words signifying a special skill that are worn on U.S. Army uniforms. On the [[Army Combat Uniform]], the tabs are worn above a unit's [[Shoulder Sleeve Insignia (United States Army)|shoulder patch]] and are used to identify a unit's or a soldier's special skill(s) or are worn on shoulder patches as part of a unit's unique heritage. Individual tabs are also worn as small metal arches above or below [[Awards and decorations of the United States Army|medals or ribbons]] on the [[Army Service Uniform]].\n\nTabs are valued uniquely in the U.S. Army because images rather than words are traditionally used for the [[symbol]]ism of the shoulder patch worn to identify a soldier's unit. It is only to identify an individual soldier's or a whole unit's special skill that an additional shoulder patch is worn that uses words rather than images to symbolize this skill. For example, while any member of a special forces unit will wear the unit identifying patch that includes an arrowhead, sword, lightning, and Airborne Tab, only soldiers who have completed special forces training will have been awarded and wear an additional tab containing the words \"SPECIAL FORCES\" (i.e. the Special Forces Tab).\n\nSome tabs are awarded to recognize an individual soldier's combat related skills or marksmanship and are worn by a soldier permanently. These tabs are also considered [[Badges of the United States Army|special skill badges]] and have metal equivalents that are worn on the soldier's chest if their uniform does not have a place for shoulder patches (e.g. the Army Service Uniform). Other tabs recognize a whole unit's special skill and are considered to be part of a specific unit's shoulder sleeve patch and are worn by a soldier only while they belong to that unit.<ref>[http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/Tab/Tabs.htm Pentagon.mil]</ref> The Jungle Expert Tab is unique in that while it is awarded to recognize an individual soldier's skill, it is only worn by soldiers while they belong to certain units.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmedals.com/detail.aspx?ID=5717|title=USmedals.com|publisher=|accessdate=3 March 2018}}</ref> Similarly, tabs awarded at the state level by the U.S. Army National Guard can only be worn by soldiers while they are on state-level orders.\n\n==Individual tabs==\nThere are currently four permanent individual skill/marksmanship tabs authorized for wear by the U.S. Army. In order of precedence, they are the [[Special Forces Tab]], the [[Ranger Tab]], the [[Sapper Tab]], and the [[President's Hundred Tab]]. Only three skill tabs may be worn at one time.<ref name=\"P670-1\">[http://www.apd.army.mil/pdffiles/p670_1.pdf U.S. Army Pamphlet 670\u20131: Uniform and Insignia, Guide to the Wear and Appearance of Army Uniforms and Insignia] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506235717/http://www.apd.army.mil/pdffiles/p670_1.pdf |date=6 May 2014 }}, Department of the Army, dated 31 March 2014, last accessed 7 March 2015</ref> A soldier wearing three skill tabs is said to have achieved the \"tower of power\" or a \"triple canopy\" in military slang.\n\n===Special Forces===\n[[File:SpecialForcesTabMetal.jpg|170px|thumb|Special Forces Tab]]\nThe [[Special Forces Tab]] is a service school qualification tab of the [[United States Army]], awarded to any soldier completing either the [[Special Forces Qualification Course]], or the Special Forces Detachment Officer Qualification Course. Soldiers who are awarded the Special Forces Tab are authorized to wear it for the remainder of their military careers, even when not serving in a [[United States Army Special Forces|Special Forces]] command. The Special Forces Tab can be revoked by the Chain of Command for significant violations of conduct considered contrary to the high standards expected of a Special Forces soldier (for example, DUI or other forms of misconduct).\n\nThe Special Forces Tab was created in 1983 and is an embroidered quadrant patch worn on the upper left sleeve of a military uniform. The cloth tab is {{convert|3+7/4|in|cm}} wide and is teal blue with yellow embroidered letters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qmmuseum.lee.army.mil/airborne/sf_tab.htm|title=Special Forces Tab|website=www.qmmuseum.lee.army.mil|accessdate=3 March 2018}}</ref><ref>Army Regulation 600-8-22, Section 8-49.</ref>\n\n===Ranger===\n[[File:Ranger Tab.svg|150px|thumb|Ranger Tab]]\nThe Ranger Tab is a qualification tab authorized upon completion of the [[Ranger School|U.S. Army's Ranger School]] by a member of the U.S. military, civilian personnel, or non-U.S. military personnel. The Ranger Tab was approved by the Chief of Staff, Army, on 30 October 1950. The Ranger Tab can be revoked IAW AR 600-8-22, Section 1-31, para. 13.\n\nThe full color tab is worn {{convert|1/2|in|cm}} below the shoulder seam on the left sleeve of the Army green coat. The subdued tab is worn {{convert|1/2|in|cm}} below the shoulder seam on the left sleeve of utility uniforms, field jackets and the desert battle dress uniform (DBDU). The full color tab is {{convert|2+3/8|in|cm}} long, {{convert|11/16|in|cm}} wide, with a {{convert|1/8|in|cm}} yellow border and the word \"RANGER\" inscribed in yellow letters {{convert|5/16|in|cm}} high. The subdued tab is identical, except the background is olive drab and the word \"RANGER\" is in black letters.<ref>[http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/tab/RangerTab.htm Pentagon.mil]</ref>\n\n===Sapper===\n[[File:SapperFullColorTab.jpg|150px|thumb|Sapper Tab]]\nThe Sapper Tab is a qualification tab which is authorized for graduates of the [[Sapper School|U.S. Army's Sapper School]]. The Sapper Tab was approved by the Chief of Staff, Army, on 28 June 2004. The Sapper tab can be revoked by the Engineer Commanding Officer of Ft. Leonard Wood, MO for misconduct, or not upholding the standard as an Engineer. Any requests will be processed through USASC.<ref>[http://www.wood.army.mil/sapper/document_frames/Pamphlet.doc Sapper leader course pamphlet] section III, US Army</ref><ref>[http://www.apd.army.mil/jw2/xmldemo/r670_1/main.asp#p029-1 Wear and Appearance of Army Uniforms and Insignia] US Army</ref>\n\nThe full color tab is worn {{convert|1/2|in|cm}} below the shoulder seam on the left sleeve of the Army green coat. The subdued tab is worn {{convert|1/2|in|cm}} below the shoulder seam on the left sleeve of utility uniforms, field jackets and the desert battle dress uniform (DBDU). The full color tab is {{convert|2+3/8|in|cm}} long, {{convert|11/16|in|cm}} wide, with a {{convert|1/8|in|cm}} red border and the word \"SAPPER\" inscribed in white letters {{convert|5/16|in|cm}} high. The woodland subdued tab is identical, except the background is olive drab and the word \"SAPPER\" is in black letters and the desert subdued tab has a khaki background with the word \"SAPPER\" in spice brown letters.<ref>[http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/tab/SapperTab.htm Pentagon.mil]</ref>\n\n===President's Hundred===\n[[File:Presidents 100 Metal Tab.jpg|210px|thumb|President's Hundred Tab]]\nThe [[President's Hundred Tab]] is a marksmanship tab which is authorized for soldiers who qualify among the top 100 scoring competitors in the President's Match held annually at the National Rifle Matches at Camp Perry, Ohio. This is a permanent award which will stay with the individual; there is no annual requirement to maintain the President's Hundred Tab. Most competitors will compete each year to ensure that less qualified individuals do not receive the tab.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uscg.mil/directives/cim/1000-1999/CIM_1020_6F.pdf|title=USCG.mil|publisher=|accessdate=3 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 May 1958, The National Rifle Association requested the Deputy Chief of Staff for Personnel's approval of a tab for presentation to each member of the \"President's Hundred.\" NRA's plan was to award the cloth tab together with a metal tab during the 1958 National Matches. The cloth tab was of high level interest and approved for wear on the uniform on 3 March 1958.<ref name=\"Short History\">[http://thecmp.org/wp-content/uploads/PresidentsMatchHistory1.pdf A Short History of the President's Match and the President's Hundred], by Hap Rocketto, dated 19 March 8, last accessed 26 November 2017</ref>\n\nA full-color embroidered tab of yellow {{convert|4+1/4|in|cm}} long and {{convert|5/8|in|cm}} high, with the word \"President's Hundred\" centered in {{convert|1/4|in|cm}} high green letters. The metal replica is {{convert|2|in|cm}} wide.<ref>[http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/tab/PresidentsHundredTab.htm Pentagon.mil]</ref>\n\n===Governor's X (National Guard)===\n[[File:Governors Twenty Tab-ABU.png|190px|thumb|Governor's Twenty Tab]]\nThe '''[[Marksmanship badges (United States)|Governor's Twenty Tab]]''' is a [[National Guard of the United States|state-level National Guard]] award, created in 1968, that is awarded to the top 20 shooters in a state. However, award criteria vary from state-to-state. For example, within the [[Texas Military Forces]], only eight guardsmen are presented this award for rifle, eight for pistol, two for sniper, and two for machine gun each year. Texas guardsmen compete against other Texas guardsman who have already received the award; thus, there may be one or two new recipients of this award each year. As of July 2014, 14 states have authorized the awarding of the Governor's Twenty Tab.<ref>[http://www.txmarks.org/combatprogram/governors20.htm Texas National Guard Marksmanship Program, Governor's Twenty], Texas National Guard, updated 4 Aug 11, last accessed 13 Nov 11</ref><ref>[http://www.txsg.state.tx.us/txsg-team-wins-first-place-in-2009-texas-adjutant-general%E2%80%99s-combat-pistol-sustainment-exercise-competition.aspx TXSG Team Wins First Place In 2009 Texas Adjutant General\u2019s Combat Pistol Sustainment Exercise Competition], Texas State Guard, by Maj. J. Michael Spraggins, dated 7 May 7, last accessed 13 Nov 11</ref><ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/texasmilitaryforces/11932768054/in/set-72157639729854336 Governor's 20 Sniper Competition 2014], Texas Military Forces, dated 12 January 2014, last accessed 19 January 2014</ref><ref>[http://vaguard.dodlive.mil/2014/08/07/5784/ Earning the Governor\u2019s Twenty Tab], By CPT Andrew J. Czaplicki, dated 7 August 2014, last accessed 10 January 2015</ref>\n\n[[File:Governors Twelve Tab-ABU.png|200px|thumb|Governor's Twelve/Dozen Tab]]\nIn the [[Missouri National Guard]] and [[Arizona National Guard]], the top twelve guardsman selected to represent their state at the [[Winston P. Wilson]] Rifle and Pistol Championships are awarded the '''Governor's Twelve Tab''', for Missouri guardsman, or the '''Governor's Dozen Tab''', for Arizona guardsman. These tabs are worn on the upper-left sleeve of the Army Combat Uniform below individual tabs and above unit and honor guard tabs. The Missouri National Guard also award a [[Awards and decorations of the National Guard#Missouri|Governor's Twelve Ribbon]] that accompanies the tab which is worn on dress uniforms; any guardsman who earns the award more than once wear [[Marksmanship Device|Hawthorn Cluster Devices]] on top of the ribbon.<ref name=\"MO Guard\">[http://www.moguard.com/12-14-10-tabs-and-badges-a-measure-of-marksmanship.html Tabs and Badges a Measure of Marksmanship] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140518224313/http://www.moguard.com/12-14-10-tabs-and-badges-a-measure-of-marksmanship.html |date=18 May 2014 }}, Missouri National Guard, dated 14 December 2010, last accessed 18 May 2014</ref><ref>[http://www.frontiernet.net/~ericbush/US/NG/Ng_attac.htm National Guard Devices], by Eric Bush, last accessed 18 May 2014</ref><ref>[https://www.army.mil/article/166150/Arizona_National_Guard_s_top_marksmen_awarded_Governor_s_Dozen Arizona National Guard's top marksmen awarded Governor's Dozen], Army.mil, by SGT Wesley Parrell, dated 15 April 2016, last accessed 5 February 2017</ref>\n\n[[File:Governors X Tab-ABU.png|165px|thumb|Governor's Ten Tab]]\nIn the [[Iowa National Guard]], the top ten rifle and/or pistol shooters from the state's Army and Air Force guard units, as well as local Army Reserve units, that compete at the Iowa Governor's 10 Shooting Competition are awarded the '''Governor's Ten Tab.''' Prior to 2008, the Governor's Ten Tab was awarded to the top five pistol shooters and top five rifle shooters. Today, the rifle and pistol scores are combined so only the best 10 overall shooters earn the tab.<ref>[https://www.dvidshub.net/news/66840/top-iowa-marksmen-train-fellow-red-bulls-afghans-torkham-gate#.VPH2XfnF8Zl Top Iowa marksmen train fellow Red Bulls, Afghans at Torkham Gate], Defense Video and Imagery Distribution System, by Staff Sgt Ryan Matson, dated 11 March 2011, last accessed 28 February 2015</ref>\n\nBecause these awards are state-level awards, soldiers and airmen in the National Guard under federal status ([[Title 10 of the United States Code|Title 10 of the U.S. Code]]) are not authorized to wear these awards until they return to [[Title 32 of the United States Code|Title 32 status]].<ref name=\"P670-1\"/><ref name=\"MO Guard\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Jungle (US Army Pacific)===\n{{multiple image\n|align    = right\n|direction= vertical\n|width1   = 185\n|image1   = Jungle Expert Tab.jpg\n|caption1 = Original Jungle Expert Tab\n|width2   = 150\n|image2   = Jungle Tab.svg\n|caption2 = Current Jungle Tab\n}}\n{{Stack|[[File:Jungle Expert Logo.png|thumb|right|175px|Former Jungle Expert Patch]]}}\nThe Jungle Expert Patch was often worn by graduates of the [[Jungle Operations Training Center]] (JOTC) at [[Fort Sherman]] until the school became inactive in 1999. The patch was authorized for wear by soldiers assigned to [[U.S. Army South]] who graduate from JOTC but the patch was never recognized Army-wide. In 2014, the JOTC was reopened in Hawaii and the Jungle Expert Patch was revitalized as a tab which is authorized for wear by soldiers who complete the course and are assigned to the [[U.S. Army Pacific]] [[area of responsibility]]. However the revitalized tab now simply reads 'Jungle' instead of 'Jungle Expert'.<ref>[http://www.benning.army.mil/infantry/magazine/issues/2014/Jan-Mar/Eifler.html Welcome (Back) to the Jungle], Infantry Online, Benning.armuy.mil, by COL Brian S. Eifler, dated Jan-Mar 2014 edition, last accessed 16 July 2016</ref><ref>[https://www.army.mil/article/210898/tamc_combat_medic_named_honor_grad_at_25id_jungle_school TAMC combat medic named honor grad at 25ID 'Jungle School'], www.army.mil, by Leanne Thomas, dated 7 September 2018, last accessed 23 February 2020</ref><ref>[https://www.army.mil/article/231985/not_for_the_faint_hearted_triplers_chief_judge_advocate_graduates_executive_jungle_school Not for the faint hearted: Tripler's Chief Judge Advocate graduates executive jungle school], www.army.mil, by SGT Natalie Kintz,, dated 23 January 2020, 23 February 2020</ref>  Other graduates of the course receive the tab as a souvenir.\n\n===Arctic (US Army Alaska)===\n[[File:U.S. Army Arctic Tab.png|thumb|right|140px|USARAK's Arctic Tab]]\nThe Arctic Tab is an individual skill tab earned by those who graduate from the Cold Weather Orientation Course or Cold Weather Leadership Course held at the [[Northern Warfare Training Center]].<ref>[https://www.army.mil/article/139127/Are_you_Arctic_Tough_/ Are you Arctic Tough?], www.army.mil, dated 26 November 2014, last accessed 7 May 2016</ref> The tab is authorized by [[United States Army Alaska|U.S. Army Alaska]] (USARAK) for wear on combat uniforms above the SSI of units assigned to USARAK while operating in the [[Alaska|State of Alaska]].<ref>[http://www.wainwright.army.mil/nwtc/Images/Website/NCOJournal.pdf Training for the Colld] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314104303/http://www.wainwright.army.mil/nwtc/Images/Website/NCOJournal.pdf |date=14 March 2016 }}; NCO Journal, volume 21, number 3, dated March 2012; page 26 (pdf page 8); last accessed 7 May 2016</ref>\n\n==Unit tabs==\nA [[shoulder sleeve insignia]] (SSI) is an embroidered patch worn on some uniforms of the United States Army that identifies the wearer's major formation. Unit tabs are an integral part of the SSI and are never worn separately. Soldiers are only authorized to wear the tab while assigned to the organization that prescribes wearing the SSI with the tab.\n\n===Airborne===\n{{multiple image\n|footer = Airborne Tabs\n|align  = right\n|width  = 150\n|image1 = AirborneYellowTab.gif\n|image2 = AirborneBlueandWhiteTab.jpg\n|image3 = Airborne Red Tab.jpg\n}}\nThe Airborne Tab is a part of the SSI of certain [[Airborne forces|airborne]] and [[air assault]] units. Airborne and air assault forces are [[military]] units, usually [[light infantry]], set up to be moved by [[aircraft]] and dropped into battle. Thus, they can be placed behind enemy lines and have an ability to deploy almost anywhere with little warning. The tab is worn immediately above and touching the SSI. The tabs are {{convert|2+1/2|in|cm}} long and {{convert|11/16|in|cm}} wide. The letters are {{convert|5/16|in|cm}} high.<ref>[http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/Catalog/Heraldry.aspx?HeraldryId=16088&CategoryId=20&grp=2&menu=Uniformed%20Services&ps=24&p=0 The U.S. Army Institute of Heraldry, Tabs, Airborne Tabs], tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil, last accessed 26 November 2017</ref>\n\n===Mountain===\n[[File:MTN-TAB.png|150px|thumb|Mountain Tab]]\nThe Mountain Tab is a part of the SSI of the [[10th Mountain Division]], the [[Northern Warfare Training Center]], and the [[Army National Guard]] Regional Training Institute's [[Cadre (military)|cadre]] assigned to the [[Army Mountain Warfare School]].  The 10th Mountain Division retains the Mountain Tab for historical purposes but is actually organized as a light infantry division.  For a period of time, the [[86th Infantry Brigade Combat Team|86th Infantry Brigade Combat Team (Mountain)]] was the only other unit whose SSI was authorized to incorporate the Mountain Tab, due to the nature of that [[Vermont Army National Guard]] brigade's training.  Under the [[Reorganization plan of United States Army#.22Associated units.22 training program|US Army's \"associated units\" program]], the 86th IBCT is now aligned under the 10th Mountain Division and wear that historic division's SSI.\n\nAlthough they do not wear the Mountain Tab, mountain warfare training is a basic component of the US Army's [[Ranger School]] and each US Army [[Special Forces (United States Army)|Special Forces Group]] maintain detachments that specialize in mountain warfare.\n\n===Advisor===\n[[File:US Army 1st SFAB SSI tab.png|150px|thumb|SFAB Tab]]\nOne of the US Army's newest units, the [[Security Force Assistance Brigade]]s (SFABs), was authorized a unit SSI that incorporates a unique tab that was initially embroidered with the words \"ADVISE - ASSIST.\" Shortly after the SFAB's SSI was authorized for wear, the tab was changed to read \"COMBAT ADVISOR\".<ref name=\"1st SFAB SSI\">[https://www.facebook.com/1SFAB/photos/a.1768924863407411.1073741827.1767763830190181/1802696690030228/?type=3&theater The 1st Security Force Assistance Brigade official Facebook page, New Shoulder Sleeve Insignia], dated 1 November 2017, last accessed 3 November 2017</ref> The SFAB SSI was changed again sometime before the 1st SFAB's official activation ceremony and their unit tab now reads simply \"ADVISOR\".<ref name=\"1st SFAB Activation Ceremony\">[https://www.army.mil/article/200244/1st_sfab_hosts_activation_ceremony_heraldry_announced 1st SFAB hosts activation ceremony; Heraldry announced], Army.mil, dated 8 February 2018, last accessed 2 March 2018</ref>\n\n===Honor Guard===\n{{multiple image\n|footer = Honor Guard Tabs\n|align  = right\n|width  = 180\n|image1 = HonorGuardTab1Bn3InfRegtTab.jpg\n|alt1   = Honor Guard Tab of the 3rd Inf Reg\n|caption1 = Honor Guard Tab of the 3rd Infantry Regiment\n|image2 = Honor Guard Blue on White Tab.jpg\n|alt2   = Honor Guard Tab for select units\n|caption2 = Honor Guard Tab for select units\n|image3 = ARNG Honor Guard Tab.png\n|alt3  = ARNG Honor Guard Tab\n|caption3 = Army National Guard Honor Guard Tab for select units\n}}\nThe Honor Guard Tab is a part of the SSI of the [[3d US Infantry Regiment (The Old Guard)|3rd U.S. Infantry Regiment (The Old Guard)]] and other selected units with ceremonial duties. The tab had been worn by the Honor Guard Company of the 1st Battle Group, 3d Infantry (The Old Guard) since early 1950. It was officially approved for wear by the Deputy Chief of Staff for Personnel (DCSPER) on 14 October 1959. The 3rd Infantry's tab is ultramarine blue {{convert|3+7/8|in|cm}} long and {{convert|11/16|in|cm}} high, the designation \"HONOR GUARD\" in white letters {{convert|5/16|in|cm}} high. The subdued tab is identical, except the background is olive drab and the letters are black.<ref>[http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/Catalog/Heraldry.aspx?HeraldryId=16089&CategoryId=20&grp=2&menu=Uniformed%20Services&ps=24&p=0 Honor Guard Tab for 1st Battalion, 3rd Infantry Regiment], U.S. Army Institute of Heraldry, last accessed 1 February 2015</ref>\n\nOn 16 March 1965, the DCSPER approved a white tab with ultramarine blue lettering for wear by select Honor Guard units throughout the U.S. Army. Proposed designs were submitted on 26 March 1965 and the color reversed version of The Old Guard's tab was approved on 19 April 1965. A subdued tab is also authorized.<ref>[http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/Catalog/Heraldry.aspx?HeraldryId=16090&CategoryId=20&grp=2&menu=Uniformed%20Services&ps=24&p=0 Honor Guard Tab for Selected Units], U.S. Army Institute of Heraldry, last accessed 1 February 2015</ref> Additionally, there are other select Army and Army National Guard units that have their own distinctive Honor Guard Tabs that are not defined in general Army uniform regulations, such as the [[United Nations Command]] Honor Guard that wear a red (or scarlet) tab with white letters on the left shoulder of their service dress uniform.<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/UNCHG/ UNC Honor Guard (Official) Facebook page], last accessed 10 July 2016</ref>\n\nOn 31 December 2012, the DCSPER approved another Honor Guard Tab for wear by select Army National Guard units. The new tab is an ultramarine blue embroidered tab with the inscription \"ARNG HONOR GUARD\" in gold {{convert|5/16|in|cm}} letters, edged with a {{convert|1/8|in|cm}} gold border.<ref>[http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/Catalog/Heraldry.aspx?HeraldryId=17675&CategoryId=20&grp=2&menu=Uniformed%20Services&ps=24&p=0 Army National Guard Honor Guard Tab], U.S. Army Institute of Heraldry, last accessed 1 February 2015</ref>\n\n===Band===\n{{multiple image\n|footer = Examples of some select unit's Army Band Tabs\n|align  = right\n|width  = 180\n|image1 = TRADOC Band Tab.png\n|caption1 = [[United States Army Training and Doctrine Command|US Army Training and Doctrine Command]] Band Tab<ref>[http://www.facebook.com/TRADOCBand?fref=ts U.S. Army Training and Doctrine Command Band Facebook page], last accessed 31 May 2017</ref>\n|image2 = US Army Reserve 100th Army Band Tab.png\n|caption2 = 100th Army Band Tab of the [[United States Army Reserve|US Army Reserve]]'s [[81st Infantry Division (United States)|81st Regional Support Command]]<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/100thArmyBand/ 100th Army Band Facebook page], last accessed 31 May 2017</ref>\n|image3 = 122nd Army Band Tab.png\n|caption3 = 122nd Army Band Tab of the [[Ohio Army National Guard]]'s [[371st Sustainment Brigade (United States)|371st Sustainment Brigade]]<ref>[http://www.122ndarmyband.com/download/122nd_Army_Band_Tab_371st_Sustainment_Brigade_Patch.jpg 371st Sustainment Brigade Shoulder Sleeve Insignia with 122nd Army Band Tab], 122nd Army Band Homepage, last accessed 31 May 2017</ref>\n}}\nSimilar to the Honor Guard Tab for select units, the Band Tab is worn by an Army band within a given unit.<ref name=\"TIOH Band\">[http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/Catalog/HeraldryList.aspx?CategoryId=211&grp=2&menu=Uniformed%20Services Distinctive Unit Insignia, Shoulder Sleeve Insignia, and Coat of Arms / Bands /], [[United States Army Institute of Heraldry]] (TIOH), last accessed 31 May 2017</ref> The exception to this is the [[United States Army Field Band|U.S. Army Field Band]] Tab which is an integral part of that unit's SSI,<ref>[http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/Catalog/HeraldryMulti.aspx?CategoryId=2967&grp=2&menu=Uniformed%20Services U.S. Army Field Band, Shoulder Sleeve Insignia], TIOH, last accessed 31 May 2017</ref> just like the Mountain Tab worn by the 10th Mountain Division. Each Army unit that has a band can have its own unique Band Tab, designed by the [[U.S. Army Institute of Heraldry]], and can only be worn with that unit's SSI.<ref name=\"TIOH Band\"/> Once a band member leaves the band to join another element of the same unit, they can no longer wear the Band Tab but continue to wear their unit's SSI. Subdued versions of each unit's Band Tab is authorized for wear with their unit's subdued SSI.<ref>[https://www.army.mil/article/130069/TRADOC_hosts_Twilight_Tattoo TRADOC hosts Twilight Tattoo (Example of U.S. Army Band Tab worn above the U.S. Army Military District of Washington / Fort McNair Shoulder Sleeve Insignia)], Army.mil, by Staff Sgt. Jennifer C. Johnson (JFHQ-NCR/MDW Public Affairs), dated 17 July 2014, last accessed 31 May 2017</ref>\n\n===Combined Division===\n[[File:US Army Combined Division Tab.png|thumb|right|180px|2nd ID's combined HQ tab]]\nOn 29 December 2015, the U.S. Army approved the wear of a black tab by soldiers assigned to Headquarters, [[2nd Infantry Division (United States)|2nd Infantry Division]] (ID). This black tab, worn immediately above the 2nd ID's SSI, is embroidered with white English and Korean letters spelling out the words \"Combined Division.\"<ref name=\"TIOH 2nd ID\">[http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/Catalog/Heraldry.aspx?HeraldryId=17971&CategoryId=20&grp=2&menu=Uniformed%20Services&ps=24&p=0 Combined Division Tab], The U.S. Army's Institute of Heraldry, dated 29 December 2015, last accessed 16 April 2016</ref> The tab is used to signify the joint nature of the new combined headquarters made up of units from the U.S. Army's 2nd ID<ref name=\"Stars & Strips\">[http://www.stripes.com/news/pacific/korea/us-south-korea-activate-1st-ever-combined-division-1.350251 US, South Korea activate 1st-ever combined division], Stars and Stripes, by Ashley Rowland, dated 3 June 2015, last accessed 16 April 2016</ref> and the [[Republic of Korea Army]]'s (ROKA) [[8th Infantry Division (South Korea)|8th ID]],<ref name=\"Stars & Strips\"/><ref name=\"ROKA OB for 16th Bde\">[http://www.army.mil/article/148361/ROKA_16th_Brigade_staff_visits_1st_ABCT/ ROKA 16th Brigade staff visits 1st ABCT], U.S. Army Homepage, by CPL SeoWon Lee, dated 12 May 2015, last accessed 16 April 2016</ref> established on 3 June 2015.<ref name=\"Stars & Strips\"/> The tab may only be worn by U.S. Army 2nd ID and ROKA 8th ID headquarters soldiers while serving within the geographical boundaries and territorial waters of the [[Republic of Korea]].<ref name=\"TIOH 2nd ID\"/>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Unofficial, obsolete, and other==\nSeveral tabs are widely worn unofficially by members of the U.S. Army. Often these tabs were worn on the underside of pocket flaps so as not to violate uniform regulations. Such tabs also appear on stickers, shirts, hats, etc. that soldiers would wear with civilian attire. These include tabs containing the words \"SNIPER\", \"AIR ASSAULT\", \"[[Artillery observer|FISTER]]\", \"SCOUT\", and \"RECON\" or \"[[Recondo|RECONDO]].\" The \"SAPPER\" tab was one of these unofficial tabs until 2004 when it became an official special skill badge/tab of the U.S. Army.\n\n===Recondo===\n{{multiple image\n|align    = right\n|direction= vertical\n|width1   = 145\n|image1   = Recondo.jpg\n|caption1 = Recondo Tab\n|width2   = 80\n|image2   = US Army ROTC Recondo Badge.png\n|caption2 = ROTC Recondo Badge\n}}\n[[Recondo]] was a [[Vietnam War]]-era title meant to designate Soldiers of the wider US Army trained in Ranger tactics but without having been sent to Ranger school. The title \"Recondo\" stood for \"Reconnaissance Commando\". The standard Recondo insignia was a downward-pointing arrowhead with \"RECONDO\" printed above. The Recondo patch was standardly worn on each graduate's right breast pocket. Recondo was also sometimes worn in the style of the more traditional shoulder tab.\n\nIn designing the unit patch for the [[Security Force Assistance Brigade]] stood up in 2018, the US Army took inspiration from the classic Recondo arrowhead design. The original unit patch design was eventually softened to less directly replicate the Recondo arrowhead patch after complaints from the US Army special forces community.<ref>{{cite web |title=Beret for Soldiers of 1st SFAB \u2013 Concern in SF Community |url=https://sof.news/sfa/sfab-beret/}}</ref> The SFAB unit patches also introduced the new \"ADVISOR\" unit level tab to the Army uniform.\n\nThe US Army ROTC still issues a Recondo Badge to cadets who successfully complete Recondo training at the Leader Development and Assessment Course.\n\n===Pershing===\n[[File:US Army Pershing Tab of the Former 56th Field Artillery Command.png|right|thumb|160px|Pershing Tab]]\nThe Pershing Tab was worn as part of the shoulder sleeve insignia (SSI) for units supporting the [[Pershing missile]] system. From 1970 to 1971 the [[56th Artillery Brigade]] wore the SSI of the Seventh Army with the Pershing tab. In 1971 the 56th FA received their own SSI that included the Pershing tab, which continued through redesignation as the 56th Field Artillery Command in 1986. The [[3rd Battalion, 9th Field Artillery Regiment]] wore the Pershing tab with the SSI of [[III Corps (United States)|III Corps]] from 1971 to 1981, then with that of the [[214th Field Artillery Brigade]] when it had a SSI created in 1981. The Pershing tab was discontinued with the deactivation of units following the elimination of the [[Pershing missile]] system in 1991.<ref>{{cite web |title=56th Field Artillery Command: Shoulder Sleeve Insignia; Distinctive Unit Insignia |work=[[United States Army Institute of Heraldry]] |url=http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/Catalog/HeraldryMulti.aspx?CategoryId=3448&grp=2&menu=Uniformed%20Services}}</ref>\n\n===Air Assault===\n[[File:US Army 11th Air Assault Tab-Historical.png|160px|thumb|SSI tab of the former 11th Air Assault Division]]\nIn 1963, the [[11th Airborne Division (United States)#Reactivation (11th Air Assault Division) and inactivation|11th Air Assault Division (Test)]] was established\u2014formed from reactivated elements of the [[11th Airborne Division (United States)|11th Airborne Division]]\u2014to explore the theory and practicality of [[air assault|helicopter assault tactics]], and was inactivated two years later when testing was completed and the [[1st Cavalry Division (United States)|1st Cavalry Division (Airmobile)]] was formed. Although this test unit wore the shoulder sleeve insignia of the 11th Airborne Division, they replaced their Airborne Tab with a unique Air Assault Tab, believed to be the first and last approved Air Assault Tab in the U.S. Army.\n\n===Army Air Forces' Command Identification===\n[[File:US Army Air Forces Command Tab-Training Command.png|180px|thumb|Example: The AAF Training Command SSI tab]]\nWith the expansion of the [[United States Army Air Forces|U.S. Army Air Forces]] (AAF) in [[World War II]], the [[:File:US Army Air Corps Hap Arnold Wings.svg|AAF SSI]] became one of the most widely worn shoulder insignias of the war.<ref name=\"AAF Tabs\">[http://www.angelfire.com/md2/patches/airforcearcs.html United States Army, Second World War, Air Force Command Arcs], angelfire.com, by Dr. Howard G. Lanham, last accessed 3 April 2020</ref>  Given the AAF SSI did not allow someone to determine which AAF command the wearer belonged, on 28 July 1945 the U.S. Army approved the use of Command Identification Tabs\u2014also known as an arc\u2014to help identify an AAF solder's command.<ref name=\"AAF Tabs\"/><ref name=\"Weatherman History\">[https://media.defense.gov/2015/Sep/11/2001329838/-1/-1/0/AFD-150911-027.pdf Air Force Weather, Our Heritage 1937 to 2012], prepared by TSgt C. A. Ravenstein (Historical Division, AW3DI, Hq AWS), dated 22 January 2012, last accessed 3 April 2020</ref><ref name=\"AAF Arcs\">[http://www.usmilitariaforum.com/forums/index.php?/topic/233240-ww2post-ww2-us-army-aaf-command-tabsarcs/ WW2/Post WW2 US Army AAF Command Tabs/Arcs], usmilitariaforum.com, last accessed 3 April 2020</ref>  These Command Identification Tabs were worn above the AAF SSI as an arc that followed the curvature of the SSI and was embroidered with the name of the AAF command in the same blue and gold colors as the SSI.<ref name=\"AAF Tabs\"/><ref name=\"Weatherman History\"/><ref name=\"AAF Arcs\"/>  The use of these Command Identification Tabs continued until the introduction of the [[United States Air Force|U.S. Air Force]] blue uniform.<ref name=\"Weatherman History\"/>\n\n===Ranger Challenge (ROTC)===\n[[File:Ranger challenge.png|thumb|160px|'''Ranger Challenge Tab''']]\nThe '''Ranger Challenge Tab''' is the only [[United States Department of the Army]] individual qualification tab awarded exclusively to [[Reserve Officers' Training Corps]] cadets. This award is presented annually to cadets who compete in regional ROTC [[Army Reserve Officers' Training Corps#Activities and clubs|Ranger Challenge competitions]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ranger Challenge Tab]]\n* [[Badges of the United States Army]]\n* [[Uniforms of the United States Army]]\n* [[United States military beret flash]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n[https://armypubs.army.mil/ProductMaps/PubForm/Details.aspx?PUB_ID=1003738] \n\n[http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/Tab/SapperTab.htm Pentagon Institute of Heraldry's Sapper Tab Page]\n* [http://usmilitary.about.com/od/army/a/sappertab.htm About.com Sapper Tab Article]\n\n{{US Army badges}}\n{{Military badges of the United States}}\n{{US Army uniforms}}\n{{Pershing missile}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tabs Of The United States Army}}\n[[Category:Awards and decorations of the United States Army]]\n[[Category:United States military badges]]\n[[Category:United States Army uniforms]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Pershing missile]]\n", "name_user": "Atfyfe", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRecondo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tabs_of_the_United_States_Army"}
{"title_page": "Chhapaak", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Chhapaak\n| image          = Chhapaak film poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Meghna Gulzar]]\n| producer       = [[Fox Star Studios]]<br/>[[Deepika Padukone]]<br/>Govind Singh Sandhu<br/>Meghna Gulzar\n| writer         = Atika Chohan<br/>Meghna Gulzar\n| starring       = [[Deepika Padukone]]<br/>[[Vikrant Massey]]\n| music          = '''Songs:'''<br/>[[Shankar\u2013Ehsaan\u2013Loy]]<br/>'''Score:'''<br/>Shankar\u2013Ehsaan\u2013Loy<br/>Tubby\n| cinematography = Malay Prakash\n| editing        = Nitin Baid\n| studio         = [[Fox Star Studios]]<br/>Ka Productions<br/>Mriga Films\n| distributor    = Fox Star Studios\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|2020|01|10}}\n| runtime        = 120 minutes<ref>{{cite web | url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/chhapaak-2020 | title=Chhapaak (2020) | website=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | accessdate=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n| country        = [[India]]\n| budget         = {{INR}}35\u201345 crore<ref>{{cite news|last=Pal|first=Deepanjana|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/mumbai-news/chhapaak-and-tanhaji-it-s-not-a-contest/story-fea98hhNcaGmhL4HUmcgiJ.html|title=Chhapaak and Tanhaji: It\u2019s not a contest|work=Hindustan Times|date=11 January 2020|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n| gross          = {{Estimation}} {{INR}}75.44 crore<ref name=\"bo\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/chhapaak/box-office/#bh-movie-box-office|title=Chhapaak Box Office|website=Bollywood Hungama|accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref>\n| language       = [[Hindi]]\n}}\n\n'''''Chhapaak''''' ({{translation |Splash}}) is a 2020 Indian [[Hindi]]-language [[drama film]] directed by [[Meghna Gulzar]] and produced by [[Deepika Padukone]] and [[Meghna Gulzar]] in collaboration with [[Fox Star Studios]]. Based on the life of [[Laxmi Agarwal]], it stars Padukone as an [[acid attack]] survivor alongside [[Vikrant Massey]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/vikrant-massey-to-star-opposite-deepika-padukone-in-film-based-on-laxmi-agarwal-it-s-called-chhapaak/333367|title=Vikrant Massey to star opposite Deepika Padukone in film based on Laxmi Agarwal, it's called Chhapaak|publisher=[[Times Now]]|date=19 December 2018|accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe film was announced on 24 December 2018 by Padukone on her Twitter account; it marks her first production venture. Filming took place from [[March]] to [[June]] 2019 in [[New Delhi]] and [[Mumbai]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dnaindia.com/bollywood/report-prep-for-deepika-padukone-s-chhapaak-begins-meghna-gulzar-shares-first-photo-check-pic-2719652|title=Prep for Deepika Padukone's Chhapaak begins, Meghna Gulzar shares first photo, check pic|newspaper=[[Daily News and Analysis]]|date=13 February 2019|accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe film was theatrically released in India on 10 January 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://hindustantimes.com/bollywood/deepika-padukone-s-chhapaak-begins-director-meghna-gulzar-shares-first-pic/story-GvhYsFHZP9BwNbwARd5iXK.html|title=Deepika Padukone's Chhapaak begins, director Meghna Gulzar shares first pic|newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]]|date=14 February 2019|accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref> The film was allowed by the government to be exhibited without payment of taxes in the states of [[Chhattisgarh]], [[Madhya Pradesh]] and [[Rajasthan]].<ref name=\"News 18 tax free\" /><ref name=\"DB tax free\" /><ref name=\"Week Tax free\" /> It received positive reviews from critics.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dore|first=Shalini|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/asia/chhapaak-deepika-padukone-1203462409/|title=Bollywood Film 'Chhapaak' Makes Serious Splash|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=9 January 2020|accessdate=10 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Jha|first=Subhash K.|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/features/much-lauded-deepika-padukone-starrer-chhapaak-crashes-box-office-trade-experts-analyse/|title=The much lauded Deepika Padukone starrer Chhapaak crashes at the box office, trade experts analyse|website=Bollywood Hungama|date=18 January 2020|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n{{empty section|date=March 2020}}\nThe film is based on the real-life story of [[acid attack]] survivor [[Laxmi Agarwal]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Deepika Padukone tears up at 'Chhapaak' trailer launch, calls it career's most special film |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/deepika-padukone-tears-up-at-chhapaak-trailer-launch-calls-it-careers-most-special-film/articleshow/72454924.cms |accessdate=20 December 2019 |publisher=economictimes.indiatimes.com}}</ref>\n\n== Cast ==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Deepika Padukone]] as Malti<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/deepikas-next-chhapaak-is-a-story-of-undying-human-spirit/articleshow/68549587.cms|title=Deepika's next 'Chhapaak' is a story of undying human spirit|newspaper=[[Times Of India]]|date=25 March 2019|accessdate=25 March 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Vikrant Massey]] as Amol\n* Madhurjeet Sarghi as Archana Bajaj\n* [[Anand Tiwari]] as Bajaj's husband\n* Vaibhavi Upadhyaya as Minakshi\n* [[Payal Nair]] as Shiraz\n* Vishal Dahiya as Basheer Khan, the acid attacker<ref name=\"BH 9 Jan attacker\">{{cite news |last1=Hungama |first1=Bollywood |title=REVEALED: Meet the actor who plays Basheer Khan, the acid attacker in Chhapaak : Bollywood News - Bollywood Hungama |url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/bollywood/revealed-meet-actor-plays-babban-shaikh-acid-attacker-chhapaak/ |accessdate=9 January 2020 |date=8 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n* Ankit Bisht as Rajesh<ref name=\"BH 9 Jan attacker\" />\n* Geeta Agarwal\n* Manohar Teli\n* Sharvari Deshpande\n* Delzad Hivale \n* [[Anjana Om Kashyap]] (herself)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Release==\nOn 10 December 2019, the official trailer was launched by [[Fox Star Studios]]. The film was theatrically released on 10 January 2020 in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=kXVf-KLyybk|title=Chhapaak - Official Trailer - Deepika Padukone - Vikrant Massey - Meghna Gulzar - 10 January 2020|last=Fox Star Studios|via=YouTube|date=10 December 2019|accessdate=10 December 2019}}</ref>  The film was allowed by the government to be exhibited without payment of taxes in the states of [[Chhattisgarh]], [[Madhya Pradesh]] and [[Rajasthan]].<ref name=\"News 18 tax free\">{{cite news |title=\u0935\u093f\u0930\u094b\u0927 \u0915\u0947 \u092c\u0940\u091a Film 'Chapaak' Madhya Pradesh \u0914\u0930 Chhattisgarh \u092e\u0947\u0902 \u0939\u0941\u0908 Tax Free {{!}} Apna MP |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TJMtS65nRDA |accessdate=20 January 2020 |work=News 18 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"DB tax free\">{{cite news |last1=Pandey |first1=Sumit |title=\u090f\u092e\u092a\u0940-\u091b\u0924\u094d\u0924\u0940\u0938\u0917\u0922\u093c \u092e\u0947\u0902 '\u091b\u092a\u093e\u0915' \u091f\u0948\u0915\u094d\u0938 \u092b\u094d\u0930\u0940, \u092d\u093e\u091c\u092a\u093e \u0928\u0947\u0924\u093e \u0928\u0947 \u0915\u0939\u093e- \u0926\u0940\u092a\u093f\u0915\u093e \u0915\u093e \u0915\u093e\u092e \u0928\u093e\u091a\u0928\u0947 \u0915\u093e \u0939\u0948, \u0935\u0947 \u0935\u0939\u0940 \u0915\u0930\u0947\u0902 |url=https://www.bhaskar.com/mp/bhopal/news/deepika-padukones-film-chhapak-is-tax-free-just-a-day-before-its-release-126475747.html |accessdate=20 January 2020 |work=Dainik Bhaskar |date=9 January 2020 |language=hi}}</ref><ref name=\"Week Tax free\">{{cite news |title='Chhapaak' declared tax-free in Rajasthan |url=https://www.theweek.in/news/entertainment/2020/01/11/chhapaak-declared-tax-free-rajasthan.html |accessdate=20 January 2020 |work=The Week |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 January 2020, Padukone joined a protest-gathering at [[Jawaharlal Nehru University]] against the [[2020 JNU Attack]] against left wing students and passage of [[Citizenship (Amendment) Act, 2019|CAA 2019]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://theprint.in/india/deepika-padukone-shows-up-at-jnu-protest-sparks-twitter-calls-for-boycott-of-chhapaak/346150/|title=Deepika Padukone shows up at JNU protest, sparks Twitter calls for boycott of 'Chhapaak'|last=|first=|date=8 January 2020|website=The Print|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=8 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Bollywood Reuters 8 Jan\">{{cite news |title=Bollywood A-lister backs protesting students, faces boycott calls |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-india-student-protests/bollywood-a-lister-backs-protesting-students-faces-boycott-calls-idUSKBN1Z71CU |accessdate=8 January 2020 |work=Reuters |date=8 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The visit angered BJP leaders who expressed it in social media.<ref name=\"Scroll 9 Jan\" /> Soon enough, the hashtags ''BoycottChhapaak'' and ''BlockDeepika'' began trending in Indian Twitter with members of the incumbent [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] contributing in its proliferation.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/offbeat/after-boycottchhapaak-offers-to-sponsor-movie-tickets-flood-twitter-2160828|title=After #BoycottChhapaak, Offers To Sponsor Movie Tickets Flood Twitter|website=NDTV.com|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/buzz/curious-case-of-deepika-padukone-gaining-twitter-followers-after-boycottchhapaak-blockdeepika-trend-2449957.html|title=Curious Case of Deepika Padukone Gaining Twitter Followers After #BoycottChhapaak Trends|website=News18|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/reel/949189/in-a-bid-to-boycottchhapaak-many-trolls-tweet-cancelled-movie-tickets-for-exactly-the-same-seats|title=In a bid to #BoycottChhapaak, many trolls tweet cancelled movie tickets \u2013 for exactly the same seats|last=Staff|first=Scroll|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> In response, ''ISupportDeepika'' was floated which gained greater traction and by the end of the day, her follower count had increased significantly.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-news/isupportdeepika-dominates-boycottchhapaak-twitterati-deepika-padukone/|title=#ISupportDeepika Dominates #BoycottChhapaak As Twitterati Hail Deepika Padukone's Big Step|last=Team Koimoi|date=2020-01-08|website=[[Koimoi]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> Actor [[Varun Dhawan]] talked about similar calls for boycott of his film Dilwale, and stated that the boycott may hurt the business,  so it is used as a scare tactics meant to prevent people from expressing their opinion in public. He supported Deepika in condemning the attacks stating it is wrong to not do it.<ref name=\"NDTV Dhawan 10 Jan\">{{cite news |title=\"Tactics To Scare\": Varun Dhawan On 'Boycott Chhapaak', Deepika Padukone |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/jnu-mob-attack-varun-dhawan-on-boycott-chhapaak-deepika-padukone-tactics-to-scare-2161704 |accessdate=10 January 2020 |work=NDTV.com |date=10 January 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn 8 January, social media users pointed out that filmmaker Meghna Gulzar had changed name and had changed religion of the rapists and the sisters/cousin of the rapists in the film.<ref name=\"Mumbai Mirror 9 January\" /> Several right-wing magazines, ''Swarajya'' and ''Opindia'' wrongly reported that the name of the attacker who was a Muslim in real life, was changed into a Hindu name \"Rajesh\", in the film.<ref name=\"Scroll 9 Jan\" /> BJP MP and Minister of State for Environment, Forest and Climate Change [[Babul Supriyo]] called the change deliberate and \"absolute hypocrisy\".<ref name=\"HT 9 January\" /> BJP [[South Delhi (Lok Sabha constituency)|MP from South Delhi]], [[Ramesh Bidhuri]] made calls to public for a boycott of the movie. <ref name=\"HT 9 January\">{{cite news |title=Fact check: Did Chhapaak change attacker's religion, name him Rajesh? |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/fact-check-did-chhapaak-change-attacker-s-religion-name-him-rajesh/story-BgPW9MPBmX5xPpkYeSW6hL.html |accessdate=9 January 2020 |work=Hindustan Times |date=8 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> BJP MP [[Subramanian Swamy]] called it a defamation and informed legal action against the makers for this.<ref name=\"Scroll 9 Jan\" />''Mumbai Mirror'' reported that in past the filmmakers making films based on real life incidents had the liberty to change the names as well as the storyline in their films.<ref name=\"Mumbai Mirror 9 January\" /> The visit to JNU by Deepika was seen by ''Mumbai Mirror'' as the reason for an aggressive stand taken against the film.<ref name=\"Mumbai Mirror 9 January\">{{cite news |title=Chhapaak finds itself in a new controversy, director Meghna Gulzar trolled over changing acid attacker's religion |url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/chhapaak-finds-itself-in-a-new-controversy-director-meghna-gulzar-trolled-over-changing-acid-attackers-religion/articleshow/73155705.cms |accessdate=9 January 2020 |work=Mumbai Mirror |date=9 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> These claims were debunked by the co founder of ''Newslaundry'', [[Abhinandan Sekhri]], who had watched a special screening of the film Chhapaak in Delhi. He stated that the claims of the attacker belonging to the Hindu religion were false, since the movie showed him as a Muslim.<ref name=\"Scroll 9 Jan\" /> Journalist Radhika Sharma from PTI reported that Rajesh was the name of Malti's boyfriend. The acid attacker was called Bashir Khan urf Babboo in the film.<ref name=\"Scroll 9 Jan\">{{cite news |last1=Pooja Chaudhuri |first1=AltNews in |title=No, Deepika Padukone's 'Chhapaak' does not portray Muslim acid attack convict as Hindu named Rajesh |url=https://scroll.in/article/949250/no-deepika-padukones-chhapaak-does-not-portray-acid-attack-convict-as-a-hindu-named-rajesh |accessdate=9 January 2020 |work=Scroll.in |date=9 January 2020}}</ref> \n\nAdvocate Aparna Bhat, who represented Agarwal in the case fought at Patiala House Courts, pursued legal action against the makers for not mentioning her in the film, \"to protect her identity and preserve her integrity\".<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/chhapaak-laxmi-agarwals-lawyer-to-take-legal-action-against-the-makers-of-the-deepika-padukone-starrer/articleshow/73165086.cms/|title='Chhapaak': Laxmi Agarwal's lawyer to take legal action against the makers of the Deepika Padukone starrer |date=9 January 2020|via= TIMES OF INDIA|accessdate=9 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite news |title= Lawyer Who Represented Acid Attack Survivor Laxmi Agarwal May Sue Chhapaak Makers  |url=https://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/lawyer-aparna-bhat-who-represented-acid-attack-survivor-laxmi-agarwal-may-sue-deepikas-chhapaak-make-2161071 |accessdate=9 January 2020 | via= NDTV |date=9 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==                             \nOn the [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds a rating of 86% based on 14 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/chhapaak|title=Chhapaak (2020)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref> Teo Bugbee of ''[[The New York Times]]'' reviewed that ''Chhapaak'' \"succeeds in balancing extremes. It is at once a pleasing and buoyant inspirational story, and a realistic depiction of the brutal aftermath of acid attacks.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Bugbee |first=Teo |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/10/movies/chhapaak-review.html|title=Chhapaak Review: Life and Activism After an Acid Attack |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=10 January 2020 |access-date=10 January 2020 }}</ref> Shubhra Gupta of ''[[The Indian Express]]'' credited the film for portraying \"drama without dreaded melodrama\" and highlighted Padukone's \"solid, realised performance\"\nto be its prime asset.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gupta |first=Shubhra |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/movie-review/chhapaak-movie-review-rating-deepika-padukone-6207416/|title=Chhapaak movie review: Deepika Padukone delivers a solid, realised performance |work=The Indian Express |date=9 January 2020 |access-date=9 January 2020 }}</ref> \nAnna M.M.Vetticad of [[Firstpost|first post]] in a mixed review wrote\"The blend Massey achieves is what Chhapaak needed as a whole. Without that, what we are left with are good intentions, a heart in the right place, a major star taking a huge risk with an unorthodox role and a bunch of pluses that somehow do not come together to deliver an immersive experience.\"\n<ref>https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/bollywood/chhapaak-movie-review-deepika-padukones-acid-attack-saga-has-its-moments-but-not-enough-7881341.html</ref>\nWriting for ''[[The Hindu]]'', [[Namrata Joshi]] summarised that \"Padukone\u2019s performance and Meghna Gulzar\u2019s direction ensure that Chhapaak is like a splash that leaves you misty with emotions, if not entirely drenched\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Joshi |first=Namrata |url=https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/movies/chhapaak-movie-review-an-emotional-force/article30526270.ece|title='Chhapaak' movie review: An emotional force |work=The Hindu |date=10 January 2020 |access-date=10 January 2020 }}</ref> Ankur Pathak of ''[[HuffPost]]'' labelled it \"a quietly powerful social commentary, a film that never allows you to be comfortable\" and considered Padukone's performance to be a career best.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pathak |first=Ankur |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.in/entry/chhapaak-movie-review-deepika-padukone-delivers-her-career-best-in-this-quietly-powerful-drama_in_5e162f52c5b600960c5f00a5|title='Chhapaak' Movie Review: Deepika Padukone Delivers Her Career Best In This Quietly Powerful Drama |work=HuffPost |date=9 January 2020 |access-date=10 January 2020 }}</ref>\n\nUday Bhatia of ''[[Mint (newspaper)|Mint]]'' wrote that it \"earnestly highlights a depressingly common horror\", adding that it \"deals squarely with its subject without quite transcending it\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Bhatia |first=Uday |url=https://www.livemint.com/industry/media/film-review-chhapaak-earnestly-highlights-a-depressingly-common-horror-11578567643892.html|title=Film review: 'Chhapaak' earnestly highlights a depressingly common horror |work=Mint |date=10 January 2020 |access-date=10 January 2020 }}</ref> In a mixed review, [[Anupama Chopra]] praised Padukone's performance but added that the film \"hovers dangerously close to becoming a public service announcement. The messaging becomes bigger than the movie, which reduces the impact\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Chopra |first=Anupama |url=https://www.filmcompanion.in/chhapaak-movie-review-despite-deepika-padukones-strong-performance-the-film-doesnt-feel-urgent-enough/|title=Chhapaak Movie Review: Despite Deepika Padukone's Strong Performance, The Film Doesn't Feel Urgent Enough |website=Film Companion |date=10 January 2020 |access-date=10 January 2020 }}</ref> Conversely, Sukanya Verma of [[Rediff.com]] commended Gulzar for documenting \"''Chhapaak''{{'}}s grim reality barefacedly without losing sight of its character's quiet determination to fight the reasons that make such heinous crimes possible in the first place\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Verma |first=Sukanya |url=https://www.rediff.com/movies/review/chhapaak-review/20200109.htm|title=Chhapaak review |website=Rediff.com |date=10 January 2020 |access-date=10 January 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n''Chhapaak'' earned {{INR}}4.77 crore at the domestic box office on its opening day. On the second day, the film collected \u20b96.90 crore. On the third day, the film collected \u20b97.35 crore,taking total opening weekend collection to \u20b919.02 crore.<ref name=\"bo\" />\n\n{{As of|2020|2|7}}, with a net of {{INR}}40.57 crore in India and {{INR}}14.87 crore overseas, the film has a worldwide collection of {{INR}}55.44 crore.it proved a disaster at box office. <ref name=\"bo\" />\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Chhapaak\n| type         = soundtrack\n| artist       = [[Shankar\u2013Ehsaan\u2013Loy]]\n| cover        = \n| alt          = \n| released     = 14 January 2020<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jiosaavn.com/album/chhapaak/k,nrfhsg5rY_|title=Chhapaak - Original Motion Picture Soundtrack |publisher=Jio Saavn}}</ref>\n| recorded     = 2018\u20132019\n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length       = 12:41\n| language     = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| label        = [[Zee Music Company]]\n| producer     = \n| prev_title   = [[The Zoya Factor (film)|The Zoya Factor]]\n| prev_year    = 2019\n| year         = 2020\n| next_title   = [[Panga (film)|Panga]]\n| next_year    = 2020\n| misc       = {{External media\n | audio1     = {{YouTube|pK-qem25zvg|Official Audio Jukebox}}\n}}}}\n\nThe film's music is composed by [[Shankar\u2013Ehsaan\u2013Loy]] while lyrics are written by [[Gulzar]].\n\n{{Tracklist\n| headline     = Track listing\n| total_length = 12:41\n| extra_column=Singer(s)\n| title1  = Nok Jhok\n| extra1  = [[Siddharth Mahadevan]]\n| length1 = 3:58\n| title2  = Chhapaak - Title Track\n| extra2  = [[Arijit Singh]]\n| length2 = 4:39\n| title3  = Khulne Do\n| extra3  = Arijit Singh\n| length3 = 2:40\n| title4  = Sab Jhulas Gaya\n| extra4  = Arijit Singh\n| length4 = 1:24\n}}\n\n== Impact ==\nFollow\u0456ng the f\u0456lm's release, the state of [[Uttarakhand]] announced a new pens\u0456on scheme for ac\u0456d attack surv\u0456vors.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/amp/movies/bollywood/story/chhapaak-impact-uttarakhand-announces-to-start-a-pension-scheme-for-acid-attack-survivors-1636123-2020-01-12|title=Chhapaak impact: Uttarakhand to start a pension scheme for acid attack survivors|publisher=India Today|date=12 January 2020|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/deepika-padukones-chhapaak-inspires-uttarakhand-to-start-a-pension-scheme-for-acid-attack-survivors/articleshow/73210914.cms|title=Deepika Padukone's 'Chhapaak' inspires Uttarakhand to start a pension scheme for acid attack survivors|publisher=The Times of India|date=12 January 2020|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2020/jan/11/uttarakhand-announces-pension-for-acid-attack-survivors-in-state-after-release-of-chhapaak-2088299.amp |title=Uttarakhand announces pension for acid attack survivors in state after release of 'Chhapaak'|publisher=New Indian Express|date=12 January 2020|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|tt9614460}}\n*{{Bollywood Hungama title|https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/chhapaak/}}\n*{{Rotten Tomatoes|https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/chhapaak}}\n{{Meghna Gulzar filmography}}\n\n[[Category:2020 films]]\n[[Category:2020s biographical films]]\n[[Category:2020s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about women in India]]\n[[Category:Films based on real people]]\n[[Category:Fox Star Studios films]]\n[[Category:Films about violence against women]]\n[[Category:Films about domestic violence]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Delhi]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Mumbai]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Chhapaak\n| image          = Chhapaak film poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Meghna Gulzar]]\n| producer       = [[Fox Star Studios]]<br/>[[Deepika Padukone]]<br/>Govind Singh Sandhu<br/>Meghna Gulzar\n| writer         = Atika Chohan<br/>Meghna Gulzar\n| starring       = [[Deepika Padukone]]<br/>[[Vikrant Massey]]\n| music          = '''Songs:'''<br/>[[Shankar\u2013Ehsaan\u2013Loy]]<br/>'''Score:'''<br/>Shankar\u2013Ehsaan\u2013Loy<br/>Tubby\n| cinematography = Malay Prakash\n| editing        = Nitin Baid\n| studio         = [[Fox Star Studios]]<br/>Ka Productions<br/>Mriga Films\n| distributor    = Fox Star Studios\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|2020|01|10}}\n| runtime        = 120 minutes<ref>{{cite web | url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/chhapaak-2020 | title=Chhapaak (2020) | website=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | accessdate=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n| country        = [[India]]\n| budget         = {{INR}}35\u201345 crore<ref>{{cite news|last=Pal|first=Deepanjana|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/mumbai-news/chhapaak-and-tanhaji-it-s-not-a-contest/story-fea98hhNcaGmhL4HUmcgiJ.html|title=Chhapaak and Tanhaji: It\u2019s not a contest|work=Hindustan Times|date=11 January 2020|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n| gross          = {{Estimation}} {{INR}}55.44 crore<ref name=\"bo\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/chhapaak/box-office/#bh-movie-box-office|title=Chhapaak Box Office|website=Bollywood Hungama|accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref>\n| language       = [[Hindi]]\n}}\n\n'''''Chhapaak''''' ({{translation |Splash}}) is a 2020 Indian [[Hindi]]-language [[drama film]] directed by [[Meghna Gulzar]] and produced by [[Deepika Padukone]] and [[Meghna Gulzar]] in collaboration with [[Fox Star Studios]]. Based on the life of [[Laxmi Agarwal]], it stars Padukone as an [[acid attack]] survivor alongside [[Vikrant Massey]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/vikrant-massey-to-star-opposite-deepika-padukone-in-film-based-on-laxmi-agarwal-it-s-called-chhapaak/333367|title=Vikrant Massey to star opposite Deepika Padukone in film based on Laxmi Agarwal, it's called Chhapaak|publisher=[[Times Now]]|date=19 December 2018|accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe film was announced on 24 December 2018 by Padukone on her Twitter account; it marks her first production venture. Filming took place from [[March]] to [[June]] 2019 in [[New Delhi]] and [[Mumbai]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dnaindia.com/bollywood/report-prep-for-deepika-padukone-s-chhapaak-begins-meghna-gulzar-shares-first-photo-check-pic-2719652|title=Prep for Deepika Padukone's Chhapaak begins, Meghna Gulzar shares first photo, check pic|newspaper=[[Daily News and Analysis]]|date=13 February 2019|accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe film was theatrically released in India on 10 January 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://hindustantimes.com/bollywood/deepika-padukone-s-chhapaak-begins-director-meghna-gulzar-shares-first-pic/story-GvhYsFHZP9BwNbwARd5iXK.html|title=Deepika Padukone's Chhapaak begins, director Meghna Gulzar shares first pic|newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]]|date=14 February 2019|accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref> The film was allowed by the government to be exhibited without payment of taxes in the states of [[Chhattisgarh]], [[Madhya Pradesh]] and [[Rajasthan]].<ref name=\"News 18 tax free\" /><ref name=\"DB tax free\" /><ref name=\"Week Tax free\" /> It received positive reviews from critics.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dore|first=Shalini|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/asia/chhapaak-deepika-padukone-1203462409/|title=Bollywood Film 'Chhapaak' Makes Serious Splash|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=9 January 2020|accessdate=10 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Jha|first=Subhash K.|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/features/much-lauded-deepika-padukone-starrer-chhapaak-crashes-box-office-trade-experts-analyse/|title=The much lauded Deepika Padukone starrer Chhapaak crashes at the box office, trade experts analyse|website=Bollywood Hungama|date=18 January 2020|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n{{empty section|date=March 2020}}\nThe film is based on the real-life story of [[acid attack]] survivor [[Laxmi Agarwal]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Deepika Padukone tears up at 'Chhapaak' trailer launch, calls it career's most special film |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/deepika-padukone-tears-up-at-chhapaak-trailer-launch-calls-it-careers-most-special-film/articleshow/72454924.cms |accessdate=20 December 2019 |publisher=economictimes.indiatimes.com}}</ref>\n\n== Cast ==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Deepika Padukone]] as Malti<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/deepikas-next-chhapaak-is-a-story-of-undying-human-spirit/articleshow/68549587.cms|title=Deepika's next 'Chhapaak' is a story of undying human spirit|newspaper=[[Times Of India]]|date=25 March 2019|accessdate=25 March 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Vikrant Massey]] as Amol\n* Madhurjeet Sarghi as Archana Bajaj\n* [[Anand Tiwari]] as Bajaj's husband\n* Vaibhavi Upadhyaya as Minakshi\n* [[Payal Nair]] as Shiraz\n* Vishal Dahiya as Basheer Khan, the acid attacker<ref name=\"BH 9 Jan attacker\">{{cite news |last1=Hungama |first1=Bollywood |title=REVEALED: Meet the actor who plays Basheer Khan, the acid attacker in Chhapaak : Bollywood News - Bollywood Hungama |url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/bollywood/revealed-meet-actor-plays-babban-shaikh-acid-attacker-chhapaak/ |accessdate=9 January 2020 |date=8 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n* Ankit Bisht as Rajesh<ref name=\"BH 9 Jan attacker\" />\n* Geeta Agarwal\n* Manohar Teli\n* Sharvari Deshpande\n* Delzad Hivale \n* [[Anjana Om Kashyap]] (herself)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Release==\nOn 10 December 2019, the official trailer was launched by [[Fox Star Studios]]. The film was theatrically released on 10 January 2020 in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=kXVf-KLyybk|title=Chhapaak - Official Trailer - Deepika Padukone - Vikrant Massey - Meghna Gulzar - 10 January 2020|last=Fox Star Studios|via=YouTube|date=10 December 2019|accessdate=10 December 2019}}</ref>  The film was allowed by the government to be exhibited without payment of taxes in the states of [[Chhattisgarh]], [[Madhya Pradesh]] and [[Rajasthan]].<ref name=\"News 18 tax free\">{{cite news |title=\u0935\u093f\u0930\u094b\u0927 \u0915\u0947 \u092c\u0940\u091a Film 'Chapaak' Madhya Pradesh \u0914\u0930 Chhattisgarh \u092e\u0947\u0902 \u0939\u0941\u0908 Tax Free {{!}} Apna MP |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TJMtS65nRDA |accessdate=20 January 2020 |work=News 18 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"DB tax free\">{{cite news |last1=Pandey |first1=Sumit |title=\u090f\u092e\u092a\u0940-\u091b\u0924\u094d\u0924\u0940\u0938\u0917\u0922\u093c \u092e\u0947\u0902 '\u091b\u092a\u093e\u0915' \u091f\u0948\u0915\u094d\u0938 \u092b\u094d\u0930\u0940, \u092d\u093e\u091c\u092a\u093e \u0928\u0947\u0924\u093e \u0928\u0947 \u0915\u0939\u093e- \u0926\u0940\u092a\u093f\u0915\u093e \u0915\u093e \u0915\u093e\u092e \u0928\u093e\u091a\u0928\u0947 \u0915\u093e \u0939\u0948, \u0935\u0947 \u0935\u0939\u0940 \u0915\u0930\u0947\u0902 |url=https://www.bhaskar.com/mp/bhopal/news/deepika-padukones-film-chhapak-is-tax-free-just-a-day-before-its-release-126475747.html |accessdate=20 January 2020 |work=Dainik Bhaskar |date=9 January 2020 |language=hi}}</ref><ref name=\"Week Tax free\">{{cite news |title='Chhapaak' declared tax-free in Rajasthan |url=https://www.theweek.in/news/entertainment/2020/01/11/chhapaak-declared-tax-free-rajasthan.html |accessdate=20 January 2020 |work=The Week |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 January 2020, Padukone joined a protest-gathering at [[Jawaharlal Nehru University]] against the [[2020 JNU Attack]] against left wing students and passage of [[Citizenship (Amendment) Act, 2019|CAA 2019]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://theprint.in/india/deepika-padukone-shows-up-at-jnu-protest-sparks-twitter-calls-for-boycott-of-chhapaak/346150/|title=Deepika Padukone shows up at JNU protest, sparks Twitter calls for boycott of 'Chhapaak'|last=|first=|date=8 January 2020|website=The Print|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=8 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Bollywood Reuters 8 Jan\">{{cite news |title=Bollywood A-lister backs protesting students, faces boycott calls |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-india-student-protests/bollywood-a-lister-backs-protesting-students-faces-boycott-calls-idUSKBN1Z71CU |accessdate=8 January 2020 |work=Reuters |date=8 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The visit angered BJP leaders who expressed it in social media.<ref name=\"Scroll 9 Jan\" /> Soon enough, the hashtags ''BoycottChhapaak'' and ''BlockDeepika'' began trending in Indian Twitter with members of the incumbent [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] contributing in its proliferation.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/offbeat/after-boycottchhapaak-offers-to-sponsor-movie-tickets-flood-twitter-2160828|title=After #BoycottChhapaak, Offers To Sponsor Movie Tickets Flood Twitter|website=NDTV.com|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/buzz/curious-case-of-deepika-padukone-gaining-twitter-followers-after-boycottchhapaak-blockdeepika-trend-2449957.html|title=Curious Case of Deepika Padukone Gaining Twitter Followers After #BoycottChhapaak Trends|website=News18|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/reel/949189/in-a-bid-to-boycottchhapaak-many-trolls-tweet-cancelled-movie-tickets-for-exactly-the-same-seats|title=In a bid to #BoycottChhapaak, many trolls tweet cancelled movie tickets \u2013 for exactly the same seats|last=Staff|first=Scroll|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> In response, ''ISupportDeepika'' was floated which gained greater traction and by the end of the day, her follower count had increased significantly.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-news/isupportdeepika-dominates-boycottchhapaak-twitterati-deepika-padukone/|title=#ISupportDeepika Dominates #BoycottChhapaak As Twitterati Hail Deepika Padukone's Big Step|last=Team Koimoi|date=2020-01-08|website=[[Koimoi]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> Actor [[Varun Dhawan]] talked about similar calls for boycott of his film Dilwale, and stated that the boycott may hurt the business,  so it is used as a scare tactics meant to prevent people from expressing their opinion in public. He supported Deepika in condemning the attacks stating it is wrong to not do it.<ref name=\"NDTV Dhawan 10 Jan\">{{cite news |title=\"Tactics To Scare\": Varun Dhawan On 'Boycott Chhapaak', Deepika Padukone |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/jnu-mob-attack-varun-dhawan-on-boycott-chhapaak-deepika-padukone-tactics-to-scare-2161704 |accessdate=10 January 2020 |work=NDTV.com |date=10 January 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn 8 January, social media users pointed out that filmmaker Meghna Gulzar had changed name and had changed religion of the rapists and the sisters/cousin of the rapists in the film.<ref name=\"Mumbai Mirror 9 January\" /> Several right-wing magazines, ''Swarajya'' and ''Opindia'' wrongly reported that the name of the attacker who was a Muslim in real life, was changed into a Hindu name \"Rajesh\", in the film.<ref name=\"Scroll 9 Jan\" /> BJP MP and Minister of State for Environment, Forest and Climate Change [[Babul Supriyo]] called the change deliberate and \"absolute hypocrisy\".<ref name=\"HT 9 January\" /> BJP [[South Delhi (Lok Sabha constituency)|MP from South Delhi]], [[Ramesh Bidhuri]] made calls to public for a boycott of the movie. <ref name=\"HT 9 January\">{{cite news |title=Fact check: Did Chhapaak change attacker's religion, name him Rajesh? |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/fact-check-did-chhapaak-change-attacker-s-religion-name-him-rajesh/story-BgPW9MPBmX5xPpkYeSW6hL.html |accessdate=9 January 2020 |work=Hindustan Times |date=8 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> BJP MP [[Subramanian Swamy]] called it a defamation and informed legal action against the makers for this.<ref name=\"Scroll 9 Jan\" />''Mumbai Mirror'' reported that in past the filmmakers making films based on real life incidents had the liberty to change the names as well as the storyline in their films.<ref name=\"Mumbai Mirror 9 January\" /> The visit to JNU by Deepika was seen by ''Mumbai Mirror'' as the reason for an aggressive stand taken against the film.<ref name=\"Mumbai Mirror 9 January\">{{cite news |title=Chhapaak finds itself in a new controversy, director Meghna Gulzar trolled over changing acid attacker's religion |url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/chhapaak-finds-itself-in-a-new-controversy-director-meghna-gulzar-trolled-over-changing-acid-attackers-religion/articleshow/73155705.cms |accessdate=9 January 2020 |work=Mumbai Mirror |date=9 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> These claims were debunked by the co founder of ''Newslaundry'', [[Abhinandan Sekhri]], who had watched a special screening of the film Chhapaak in Delhi. He stated that the claims of the attacker belonging to the Hindu religion were false, since the movie showed him as a Muslim.<ref name=\"Scroll 9 Jan\" /> Journalist Radhika Sharma from PTI reported that Rajesh was the name of Malti's boyfriend. The acid attacker was called Bashir Khan urf Babboo in the film.<ref name=\"Scroll 9 Jan\">{{cite news |last1=Pooja Chaudhuri |first1=AltNews in |title=No, Deepika Padukone's 'Chhapaak' does not portray Muslim acid attack convict as Hindu named Rajesh |url=https://scroll.in/article/949250/no-deepika-padukones-chhapaak-does-not-portray-acid-attack-convict-as-a-hindu-named-rajesh |accessdate=9 January 2020 |work=Scroll.in |date=9 January 2020}}</ref> \n\nAdvocate Aparna Bhat, who represented Agarwal in the case fought at Patiala House Courts, pursued legal action against the makers for not mentioning her in the film, \"to protect her identity and preserve her integrity\".<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/chhapaak-laxmi-agarwals-lawyer-to-take-legal-action-against-the-makers-of-the-deepika-padukone-starrer/articleshow/73165086.cms/|title='Chhapaak': Laxmi Agarwal's lawyer to take legal action against the makers of the Deepika Padukone starrer |date=9 January 2020|via= TIMES OF INDIA|accessdate=9 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite news |title= Lawyer Who Represented Acid Attack Survivor Laxmi Agarwal May Sue Chhapaak Makers  |url=https://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/lawyer-aparna-bhat-who-represented-acid-attack-survivor-laxmi-agarwal-may-sue-deepikas-chhapaak-make-2161071 |accessdate=9 January 2020 | via= NDTV |date=9 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==                             \nOn the [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds a rating of 86% based on 14 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/chhapaak|title=Chhapaak (2020)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref> Teo Bugbee of ''[[The New York Times]]'' reviewed that ''Chhapaak'' \"succeeds in balancing extremes. It is at once a pleasing and buoyant inspirational story, and a realistic depiction of the brutal aftermath of acid attacks.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Bugbee |first=Teo |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/10/movies/chhapaak-review.html|title=Chhapaak Review: Life and Activism After an Acid Attack |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=10 January 2020 |access-date=10 January 2020 }}</ref> Shubhra Gupta of ''[[The Indian Express]]'' credited the film for portraying \"drama without dreaded melodrama\" and highlighted Padukone's \"solid, realised performance\"\nto be its prime asset.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gupta |first=Shubhra |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/movie-review/chhapaak-movie-review-rating-deepika-padukone-6207416/|title=Chhapaak movie review: Deepika Padukone delivers a solid, realised performance |work=The Indian Express |date=9 January 2020 |access-date=9 January 2020 }}</ref> \nAnna M.M.Vetticad of [[Firstpost|first post]] in a mixed review wrote\"The blend Massey achieves is what Chhapaak needed as a whole. Without that, what we are left with are good intentions, a heart in the right place, a major star taking a huge risk with an unorthodox role and a bunch of pluses that somehow do not come together to deliver an immersive experience.\"\n<ref>https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/bollywood/chhapaak-movie-review-deepika-padukones-acid-attack-saga-has-its-moments-but-not-enough-7881341.html</ref>\nWriting for ''[[The Hindu]]'', [[Namrata Joshi]] summarised that \"Padukone\u2019s performance and Meghna Gulzar\u2019s direction ensure that Chhapaak is like a splash that leaves you misty with emotions, if not entirely drenched\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Joshi |first=Namrata |url=https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/movies/chhapaak-movie-review-an-emotional-force/article30526270.ece|title='Chhapaak' movie review: An emotional force |work=The Hindu |date=10 January 2020 |access-date=10 January 2020 }}</ref> Ankur Pathak of ''[[HuffPost]]'' labelled it \"a quietly powerful social commentary, a film that never allows you to be comfortable\" and considered Padukone's performance to be a career best.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pathak |first=Ankur |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.in/entry/chhapaak-movie-review-deepika-padukone-delivers-her-career-best-in-this-quietly-powerful-drama_in_5e162f52c5b600960c5f00a5|title='Chhapaak' Movie Review: Deepika Padukone Delivers Her Career Best In This Quietly Powerful Drama |work=HuffPost |date=9 January 2020 |access-date=10 January 2020 }}</ref>\n\nUday Bhatia of ''[[Mint (newspaper)|Mint]]'' wrote that it \"earnestly highlights a depressingly common horror\", adding that it \"deals squarely with its subject without quite transcending it\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Bhatia |first=Uday |url=https://www.livemint.com/industry/media/film-review-chhapaak-earnestly-highlights-a-depressingly-common-horror-11578567643892.html|title=Film review: 'Chhapaak' earnestly highlights a depressingly common horror |work=Mint |date=10 January 2020 |access-date=10 January 2020 }}</ref> In a mixed review, [[Anupama Chopra]] praised Padukone's performance but added that the film \"hovers dangerously close to becoming a public service announcement. The messaging becomes bigger than the movie, which reduces the impact\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Chopra |first=Anupama |url=https://www.filmcompanion.in/chhapaak-movie-review-despite-deepika-padukones-strong-performance-the-film-doesnt-feel-urgent-enough/|title=Chhapaak Movie Review: Despite Deepika Padukone's Strong Performance, The Film Doesn't Feel Urgent Enough |website=Film Companion |date=10 January 2020 |access-date=10 January 2020 }}</ref> Conversely, Sukanya Verma of [[Rediff.com]] commended Gulzar for documenting \"''Chhapaak''{{'}}s grim reality barefacedly without losing sight of its character's quiet determination to fight the reasons that make such heinous crimes possible in the first place\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Verma |first=Sukanya |url=https://www.rediff.com/movies/review/chhapaak-review/20200109.htm|title=Chhapaak review |website=Rediff.com |date=10 January 2020 |access-date=10 January 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n''Chhapaak'' earned {{INR}}4.77 crore at the domestic box office on its opening day. On the second day, the film collected \u20b96.90 crore. On the third day, the film collected \u20b97.35 crore,taking total opening weekend collection to \u20b919.02 crore.<ref name=\"bo\" />\n\n{{As of|2020|2|7}}, with a net of {{INR}}40.57 crore in India and {{INR}}14.87 crore overseas, the film has a worldwide collection of {{INR}}55.44 crore.it proved a disaster at box office. <ref name=\"bo\" />\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Chhapaak\n| type         = soundtrack\n| artist       = [[Shankar\u2013Ehsaan\u2013Loy]]\n| cover        = \n| alt          = \n| released     = 14 January 2020<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jiosaavn.com/album/chhapaak/k,nrfhsg5rY_|title=Chhapaak - Original Motion Picture Soundtrack |publisher=Jio Saavn}}</ref>\n| recorded     = 2018\u20132019\n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length       = 12:41\n| language     = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| label        = [[Zee Music Company]]\n| producer     = \n| prev_title   = [[The Zoya Factor (film)|The Zoya Factor]]\n| prev_year    = 2019\n| year         = 2020\n| next_title   = [[Panga (film)|Panga]]\n| next_year    = 2020\n| misc       = {{External media\n | audio1     = {{YouTube|pK-qem25zvg|Official Audio Jukebox}}\n}}}}\n\nThe film's music is composed by [[Shankar\u2013Ehsaan\u2013Loy]] while lyrics are written by [[Gulzar]].\n\n{{Tracklist\n| headline     = Track listing\n| total_length = 12:41\n| extra_column=Singer(s)\n| title1  = Nok Jhok\n| extra1  = [[Siddharth Mahadevan]]\n| length1 = 3:58\n| title2  = Chhapaak - Title Track\n| extra2  = [[Arijit Singh]]\n| length2 = 4:39\n| title3  = Khulne Do\n| extra3  = Arijit Singh\n| length3 = 2:40\n| title4  = Sab Jhulas Gaya\n| extra4  = Arijit Singh\n| length4 = 1:24\n}}\n\n== Impact ==\nFollow\u0456ng the f\u0456lm's release, the state of [[Uttarakhand]] announced a new pens\u0456on scheme for ac\u0456d attack surv\u0456vors.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/amp/movies/bollywood/story/chhapaak-impact-uttarakhand-announces-to-start-a-pension-scheme-for-acid-attack-survivors-1636123-2020-01-12|title=Chhapaak impact: Uttarakhand to start a pension scheme for acid attack survivors|publisher=India Today|date=12 January 2020|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/deepika-padukones-chhapaak-inspires-uttarakhand-to-start-a-pension-scheme-for-acid-attack-survivors/articleshow/73210914.cms|title=Deepika Padukone's 'Chhapaak' inspires Uttarakhand to start a pension scheme for acid attack survivors|publisher=The Times of India|date=12 January 2020|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2020/jan/11/uttarakhand-announces-pension-for-acid-attack-survivors-in-state-after-release-of-chhapaak-2088299.amp |title=Uttarakhand announces pension for acid attack survivors in state after release of 'Chhapaak'|publisher=New Indian Express|date=12 January 2020|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|tt9614460}}\n*{{Bollywood Hungama title|https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/chhapaak/}}\n*{{Rotten Tomatoes|https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/chhapaak}}\n{{Meghna Gulzar filmography}}\n\n[[Category:2020 films]]\n[[Category:2020s biographical films]]\n[[Category:2020s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about women in India]]\n[[Category:Films based on real people]]\n[[Category:Fox Star Studios films]]\n[[Category:Films about violence against women]]\n[[Category:Films about domestic violence]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Delhi]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Mumbai]]\n", "name_user": "2409:4070:499:6285::239c:58a0", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chhapaak"}
{"title_page": "Royston Smith", "text_new": "{{for|the cricketer|Royston Smith (cricketer)}}\n{{short description|British politician}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Royston Smith\n| honorific-suffix = {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|GM}} [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| office = Member of Parliament<br />for [[Southampton Itchen (UK Parliament constituency)|Southampton Itchen]]\n| term_start = 7 May 2015\n| predecessor = [[John Denham (politician)|John Denham]]\n| successor   =\n| majority = 4,498 (9.5%)<ref name=BBC2019/>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1964|5|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Harefield, Southampton]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| otherparty = [[Referendum Party]] (in 1997)\n| website = {{URL|roystonsmith.co.uk}}\n| allegiance = United Kingdom\n| branch = [[Royal Air Force]]\n| image = [[File:RoystonSmithMP.jpg]]\n}}\n\n'''Royston Matthew Smith''',<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=61230 |date=18 May 2015 |page=9122}}</ref> {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|GM}} (born 13 May 1964) is a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician and has served as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Southampton Itchen (UK Parliament constituency)|Southampton Itchen]] since the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]].<ref name=BBC2019>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000955|title=Southampton Itchen|accessdate=13 December 2019|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> Smith was previously a councillor on the [[Southampton City Council]].\n\n==Early life and career==\nSmith was born on 13 May 1964 in [[Harefield, Southampton]] to Frank Wilmot and Marie Cecilia Smith (n\u00e9e Page).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-283955|title=Smith, Royston Matthew|accessdate=29 October 2019|publisher=A & C Black}}</ref> He grew up in the suburb of [[Bitterne Park]], and attended Bitterne Park School.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.roystonsmith.co.uk/diary/royston-visits-old-school/|publisher=Royston Smith|date=22 April 2016|accessdate=29 October 2019|title=Royston visits his old school}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailyecho.co.uk/news/5729452.royston-smith-conservative-southampton-itchen/|work=Southern Daily Echo|title=Royston Smith, Conservative, Southampton Itchen|date=30 March 2010|accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe became an engineer for the [[Royal Air Force]] (RAF) in 1980, working on the [[Hawker Siddeley Nimrod]] fleet for 10 years. Smith then worked for [[British Airways]] as an aeronautical engineer at [[London Heathrow]] for 16 years.<ref name=\"Carr2015\">{{cite book|first=Tim|last=Carr|title=The Politicos Guide to the New House of Commons 2015: Profiles of the New MPs and Analysis of the 2015 General Election Results|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BVWqCQAAQBAJ&pg=PT394|date=18 May 2015|publisher=Biteback Publishing|isbn=978-1-84954-924-0|page=394}}</ref>\n\nSmith owned the local bike shop Triangle Cycles in Bitterne Park from 1993 to 2003, and was the chairman of the Triangle Traders' association.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bitternepark.info/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2390:bitterne-parker-royston-smith&catid=83:bitterne-parker&Itemid=100138|title=Bitterne Parker Royston Smith|publisher=Bitterne Park|accessdate=22 May 2017}}</ref> He founded the public relations consultancy Vigilo Ltd in 2006.<ref name=\"Carr2015\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/05933160/filing-history?page=2|title=Vigilo Ltd.|accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref> He has been a director of 3S Fire Ltd, a fire management consultancy affiliated with the HFRS since 2013.<ref name=\"Carr2015\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/08411305/officers|title=3SFire Limited|publisher=Companies House|accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Local political career==\nSmith joined the Conservative Party after the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]]. He had previously voted for the single issue [[Euroscepticism|Eurosceptic]] [[Referendum Party]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/commons/2018-01-22/debates/1BEAD2EE-F7CC-4732-A4CC-DC4D8E5D8B93/LeavingTheEuropeanUnion|title=Leaving the European Union|date=22 January 2018|accessdate=29 October 2019|publisher=parliament.uk}}</ref> He was first elected as a Conservative councillor for the Harefield ward in the 2000 [[Southampton City Council]] election. Smith had previously unsuccessfully contested the council elections in 1998 as an independent candidate and in 1999 as a Conservative.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.electionscentre.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/Southampton-1996-2012.pdf|title=Southampton Council Election Results 1996-2012|publisher=Plymouth University|accessdate=9 July 2018}}</ref> He was a cabinet member for economic development on the council between 2007 and 2010.<ref name=\"Carr2015\"/> He was the leader of the council until 2012 when the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] took over the council.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hampshire-18669774|title=Southampton City Council to axe more jobs|publisher=BBC News|date=2 July 2012|accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nSmith was appointed as chairman of [[Hampshire Fire and Rescue Service]] (HFRS) in 2009 and was re-appointed in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hantsfire.gov.uk/incidents-news-and-events/news-releases/2014/councillor-royston-smith-re-appointed-chairman-of-hampshire-fire/|title=Hampshire Fire and Rescue Service|date=6 June 2014|publisher=Hampshire Fire and Rescue Service|accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2011, while Smith was visiting the submarine [[HMS Astute (S119)]] as part of the tour, a sailor started shooting, and killed an officer. Smith intervened and helped apprehend the sailor. He was awarded the [[George Medal]] for his actions.<ref name=bbc13022096>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hampshire-13022096 |title=Council boss 'disarmed gunman' on nuclear submarine |publisher=BBC News |date=8 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hampshire-20431302 |publisher=BBC News |title=George Medals for men who tackled gunman Ryan Donovan|date=21 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nAs council leader in 2011, Smith initiated an up to 5.5% pay cut on council employees as part of a bid to cut the council's expenditure by \u00a376 million by 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2012/jan/24/southampton-council-strikes-royston-smith|work=The Guardian|title=Unions and Southampton council go head to head over cuts |last=Milmo|first=Dan|accessdate=13 December 2019|date=24 January 2012}}</ref> In response, unions took industrial action by refusing to collect rubbish in the council.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hampshire-13695474|title=Southampton refuse collectors extend strike|publisher=BBC News|date=8 June 2011|accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nSmith stood as a Conservative candidate in the [[Southampton Itchen (UK Parliament constituency)|Southampton Itchen]] constituency in the 2010 general election. He came second in the seat, losing by 192 votes to the incumbent Labour MP [[John Denham (politician)|John Denham]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/election-2010/7691686/General-Election-2010-John-Denham-scrapes-victory-in-Southampton-Itchen-seat.html|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=7 May 2010|accessdate=29 October 2019|title=General Election 2010: John Denham scrapes victory in Southampton Itchen seat|last=Wardrop|first=Murray}}</ref> Smith was elected as MP for the constituency in the subsequent 2015 general election and was re-elected in the 2017 and 2019 general elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://electionresults.parliament.uk/election/2015-05-07/results/Location/Constituency/Southampton,%20Itchen|publisher=parliament.uk|accessdate=29 October 2019|title=Southampton, Itchen - 2015 Election Results}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-eu-election-insight/leave-or-remain-brexit-bind-could-hurt-labour-in-a-snap-election-idUKKCN1VJ1HP|title=Leave or remain? Brexit bind could hurt Labour in a snap election|last=MacLellan|first=Kylie|date=29 August 2019|accessdate=29 October 2019|publisher=Reuters}}</ref> \n\n===House of Commons Select Committee Membership===  \nSmith sat on the [[Work and Pensions Select Committee]] between December 2016 and May 2017. He was a part of the [[Committees on Arms Export Controls]] between October 2017 and July 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/royston-smith/4478|title=Royston Smith MP|publisher=parliament.uk|accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe has been a member of the [[Foreign Affairs Select Committee]] since September 2017.<ref>https://members.parliament.uk/member/4478/career|accessdate=09 March 2020</ref> <ref>https://committees.parliament.uk/committee/78/foreign-affairs-committee/membership/|accessdate=09 March 2020</ref>\n\n===Remunerated outside interests===  \nSmith received regular payments of \u00a36,000 per quarter from landowners Barker Mill Estates <ref>{{cite web|url=https://barkermillestates.com/|title=Home - Barker-Mill Estates|date=29 August 2019|accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref> for most of his career as an MP. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/mps-lords-and-offices/standards-and-financial-interests/parliamentary-commissioner-for-standards/registers-of-interests/register-of-members-financial-interests/|title=Register of Members' Financial Interests|publisher=parliament.uk|accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/721697/CSPL_MPs__outside_interests_-_full_report.PDF|title=MPs' Outside Interests|publisher=Committee on Standards in Public Life|website=gov.uk|date=3 July 2018|accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref> {{Failed verification|date=March 2020}}  \n\n===Brexit===\nSmith supported [[Brexit]] in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 UK EU membership referendum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-35616946|title=EU vote: Where the cabinet and other MPs stand|publisher=BBC News|date=22 June 2016|accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref> He voted for the then Prime Minister [[Theresa May]]'s Brexit withdrawal agreement on 29 March 2019. Smith also voted against any [[Proposed referendum on the Brexit withdrawal agreement|referendum on a withdrawal agreement]] in the indicative votes on 27 March.<ref name=FT>{{cite news|url=https://ig.ft.com/brexit-exit-deal-vote/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902092554/https://ig.ft.com/brexit-exit-deal-vote/|archivedate=2 September 2019|date=29 March 2019|title=How MPs voted on May's withdrawal deal defeat|work=Financial Times}}</ref> He then voted for the Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]]'s Brexit withdrawal agreement in October.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-deal-how-my-mp-voted-labour-conservative-boris-johnson-a9167026.html|work=The Independent|title=How your MP voted for Boris Johnson's Brexit deal|date=23 October 2019|accessdate=29 October 2019|last=Buchan|first=Lizzy}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, he successful secured Government's Brexit contingency funding for Southampton after writing a letter to [[Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government]] [[James Brokenshire]]. He made the case that Brexit-related gridlock caused by disruption at south coast ports could have a major impact on hospitals and other services. Smith believed Southampton needs tens of thousands of pounds to cope with what he describes as \u201cevery eventuality\u201d in the letter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyecho.co.uk/news/17439919.mps-demand-extra-cash-for-hampshire-as-county-prepares-for-potential-no-deal-brexit-chaos/|title=MPs demand extra cash for Hampshire as county prepares for potential no-deal Brexit chaos|website=Daily Echo|language=en|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref>  A few days afterwards, Southampton was awarded \u00a3273,000 to help the port cope with the impact of Brexit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyecho.co.uk/news/17448638.city-handed-273k-to-help-port-cope-with-fallout-from-brexit/|title=City handed \u00a3273k to help port cope with fallout from Brexit|website=Daily Echo|language=en|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref>\n\n=== Campaigning for jobs and investment to Southampton ===\nSmith has been campaigning for a fair deal for Southampton since he was a [[Councillor]]. In 2010, he fought for [[Itchen College]] when the Government withdrew funding, to protect Southampton's estate regeneration programme and get investment into [[Woolston, Southampton|Woolston]] shopping parade.<ref name=\"dailyecho.co.uk\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyecho.co.uk/news/5729452.royston-smith-conservative-southampton-itchen/|title=Royston Smith, Conservative, Southampton Itchen|website=Daily Echo|language=en|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref>\n \t\nIn 2019, writing in ''The Times'', Smith associated Southampton with [[Post-industrial economy|post-industrial]] towns to make the argument that [[Government ministers|Government Ministers]] should look South not just North when it comes to Government priorities in regenerating cities.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/look-south-pm-it-s-not-just-about-helping-labour-leavers-in-the-north-xwwkhvplp|title=Look south PM, it's not just about helping Labour Leavers in the north|last=Smith|first=Royston|date=2019-02-13|access-date=2019-07-26|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nIn the House of Commons Chamber, Smith asked the Government several times what is being done to create jobs with higher pay and better prospects.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2019-03-18/debates/928B4617-5BAC-4620-9F16-E086EBA22479/Employment?highlight=jobs#contribution-EC855A49-459B-4524-8311-650C9D8F1A63)%20(https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2019-04-24/debates/D1A68F81-35D0-4D36-B91C-8FC555CCC3E6/TopicalQuestions?highlight=jobs#contribution-65A1996F-A8D6-488C-8095-A2A47E2C3A76|title=Employment - Hansard|website=hansard.parliament.uk|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref>\n\n=== Campaign to honour the Spitfire ===\nIn 2018, Smith met with the Minister with responsibility for coastal communities to discuss his campaign to honour the [[Supermarine Spitfire|Spitfire]] and how Southampton could put in a bid to help fund a fitting memorial to the iconic aircraft. [[R. J. Mitchell]] designed the Spitfire in Southampton and its first flight was from [[Eastleigh]] Airport.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.roystonsmith.co.uk/campaign-honour-spitfire-continues/|title=Campaign to honour the Spitfire continues|last=Smith|first=Royston|date=2018-03-02|website=Royston Smith - At the heart of Southampton|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March 2017, Smith held a Westminster Hall debate in Parliament calling on the Government to help fund The National Tribute to The [[Royal Air Force]] in Southampton. The debate received support from MPs on all sides of the house.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2017-03-28/debates/6EB2C2FF-A4B2-44C1-B58B-E891E37E18CE/NationalSpitfireProject?highlight=spitfire#contribution-FFD8462D-4A61-4619-AE97-65AF4D311F86|title=National Spitfire Project - Hansard|website=hansard.parliament.uk|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.roystonsmith.co.uk/royston-leads-westminster-hall-debate-spitfire/|title=Royston leads Westminster Hall debate on the Spitfire|last=Smith|first=Royston|date=2017-03-30|website=Royston Smith - At the heart of Southampton|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn 2011, Smith was stopped by police for not wearing a seat belt and later found to have been driving an uninsured car. He was fined and given six points on his driving licence.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hampshire-15864926|title=Uninsured Southampton council leader Royston Smith fined|date=23 November 2011|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=28 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter the 2015 election, [[UK Independence Party|UKIP]] candidate Kim Rose claimed that he had received data on voters in the constituency and advice from Smith to assist his campaign.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/may/31/royston-smith-faces-claims-ukip-helped-ukip-candidate|work=The Guardian|title=Conservative MP faces claims he helped Ukip candidate target Labour voters|last=Perraudin|first=Frances|date=31 May 2015|accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref> Smith denied the allegations. Police have looked into the matter and said Smith had no case to answer. Smith's local party association, Southampton Itchen Conservative Association was registered with the [[Information Commissioner's Office]], and the [[Chairman of the Conservative Party|Conservative Party Chairman]] at the time, [[Andrew Feldman, Baron Feldman of Elstree|Lord Feldman,]] wrote to complainants to say that no data protection breach had occurred.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyecho.co.uk/news/13931416.southampton-mp-in-clear-over-voter-allegations/|title=Southampton MP in clear over voter allegations|website=Daily Echo|language=en|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 February 2016, Smith was named as Britain's least active MP out of all the MPs that are newly elected in 2015 by 'The Independent'. Smith defended his record by stating that, \"I find Southampton is a challenging constituency. He added, \"Southampton is a challenging constituency and I spend my time doing as much as I can locally. I don't spend hours in the House of Commons waiting to make a three-minute speech.\" \n.<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\">{{cite news|work=The Independent|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tory-mp-royston-smith-is-least-active-among-parliaments-new-members-a6886761.html|title=This is the least active MP of Parliament's new members|date=20 February 2016|accessdate=30 December 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hampshire-35629442|title='Least active MP' defends record|date=22 February 2016|work=BBC News|accessdate=30 December 2017|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> At the same time Smith was found to have received funds for Consultancy work outside of Parliamentary business. {{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nIn December 2017, Smith suggested cyclists should only use roads with cycle lanes on them, stating that cyclists should \"consider when and where they cycle\" in order to \"make the roads safer\". The comments came after a 64-year-old cyclist died after colliding with a lorry on Portsmouth Road, Woolston. He was criticised by campaigners on the grounds that \"we should be encouraging more people to use the roads, not less\", while it was subsequently reported that Smith had recently called for \u00a311.5 million in grant funding for the city's cycling strategy, such as creating new cycle lanes, to be diverted elsewhere.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyecho.co.uk/news/15783263.MP_calls_for_cyclists_to_think_twice_before_using_busy_roads_following_fatal_crash/|title=MP calls for cyclists to think twice before using busy roads following fatal crash|date=20 December 2017|newspaper=Daily Echo|accessdate=9 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/latest-news/mp-says-cyclists-stick-cycle-lanes-rider-dies-crash-lorry-363973|title=MP says cyclists should 'stick to cycle lanes' after rider dies in crash with lorry|date=21 December 2017|newspaper=Cycling Weekly|accessdate=9 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe lives in [[Peartree (ward)|Peartree]], Southampton.<ref name=\"dailyecho.co.uk\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=royston-smith/4478 |publicwhip=Royston_Smith |theywork=royston_smith}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Denham (politician)|John Denham]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br />for [[Southampton Itchen (UK Parliament constituency)|Southampton Itchen]]|years=[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{South East Conservative Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Royston}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Southampton]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the George Medal]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force airmen]]\n[[Category:Leaders of local authorities of England]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the cricketer|Royston Smith (cricketer)}}\n{{short description|British politician}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Royston Smith\n| honorific-suffix = {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|GM}} [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| office = Member of Parliament<br />for [[Southampton Itchen (UK Parliament constituency)|Southampton Itchen]]\n| term_start = 7 May 2015\n| predecessor = [[John Denham (politician)|John Denham]]\n| successor   =\n| majority = 4,498 (9.5%)<ref name=BBC2019/>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1964|5|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Harefield, Southampton]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| otherparty = [[Referendum Party]] (in 1997)\n| website = {{URL|roystonsmith.co.uk}}\n| allegiance = United Kingdom\n| branch = [[Royal Air Force]]\n| image = [[File:RoystonSmithMP.jpg]]\n}}\n\n'''Royston Matthew Smith''',<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=61230 |date=18 May 2015 |page=9122}}</ref> {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|GM}} (born 13 May 1964) is a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician and has served as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Southampton Itchen (UK Parliament constituency)|Southampton Itchen]] since the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]].<ref name=BBC2019>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000955|title=Southampton Itchen|accessdate=13 December 2019|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> Smith was previously a councillor on the [[Southampton City Council]].\n\n==Early life and career==\nSmith was born on 13 May 1964 in [[Harefield, Southampton]] to Frank Wilmot and Marie Cecilia Smith (n\u00e9e Page).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-283955|title=Smith, Royston Matthew|accessdate=29 October 2019|publisher=A & C Black}}</ref> He grew up in the suburb of [[Bitterne Park]], and attended Bitterne Park School.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.roystonsmith.co.uk/diary/royston-visits-old-school/|publisher=Royston Smith|date=22 April 2016|accessdate=29 October 2019|title=Royston visits his old school}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailyecho.co.uk/news/5729452.royston-smith-conservative-southampton-itchen/|work=Southern Daily Echo|title=Royston Smith, Conservative, Southampton Itchen|date=30 March 2010|accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe became an engineer for the [[Royal Air Force]] (RAF) in 1980, working on the [[Hawker Siddeley Nimrod]] fleet for 10 years. Smith then worked for [[British Airways]] as an aeronautical engineer at [[London Heathrow]] for 16 years.<ref name=\"Carr2015\">{{cite book|first=Tim|last=Carr|title=The Politicos Guide to the New House of Commons 2015: Profiles of the New MPs and Analysis of the 2015 General Election Results|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BVWqCQAAQBAJ&pg=PT394|date=18 May 2015|publisher=Biteback Publishing|isbn=978-1-84954-924-0|page=394}}</ref>\n\nSmith owned the local bike shop Triangle Cycles in Bitterne Park from 1993 to 2003, and was the chairman of the Triangle Traders' association.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bitternepark.info/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2390:bitterne-parker-royston-smith&catid=83:bitterne-parker&Itemid=100138|title=Bitterne Parker Royston Smith|publisher=Bitterne Park|accessdate=22 May 2017}}</ref> He founded the public relations consultancy Vigilo Ltd in 2006.<ref name=\"Carr2015\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/05933160/filing-history?page=2|title=Vigilo Ltd.|accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref> He has been a director of 3S Fire Ltd, a fire management consultancy affiliated with the HFRS since 2013.<ref name=\"Carr2015\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/08411305/officers|title=3SFire Limited|publisher=Companies House|accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Local political career==\nSmith joined the Conservative Party after the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]]. He had previously voted for the single issue [[Euroscepticism|Eurosceptic]] [[Referendum Party]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/commons/2018-01-22/debates/1BEAD2EE-F7CC-4732-A4CC-DC4D8E5D8B93/LeavingTheEuropeanUnion|title=Leaving the European Union|date=22 January 2018|accessdate=29 October 2019|publisher=parliament.uk}}</ref> He was first elected as a Conservative councillor for the Harefield ward in the 2000 [[Southampton City Council]] election. Smith had previously unsuccessfully contested the council elections in 1998 as an independent candidate and in 1999 as a Conservative.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.electionscentre.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/Southampton-1996-2012.pdf|title=Southampton Council Election Results 1996-2012|publisher=Plymouth University|accessdate=9 July 2018}}</ref> He was a cabinet member for economic development on the council between 2007 and 2010.<ref name=\"Carr2015\"/> He was the leader of the council until 2012 when the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] took over the council.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hampshire-18669774|title=Southampton City Council to axe more jobs|publisher=BBC News|date=2 July 2012|accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nSmith was appointed as chairman of [[Hampshire Fire and Rescue Service]] (HFRS) in 2009 and was re-appointed in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hantsfire.gov.uk/incidents-news-and-events/news-releases/2014/councillor-royston-smith-re-appointed-chairman-of-hampshire-fire/|title=Hampshire Fire and Rescue Service|date=6 June 2014|publisher=Hampshire Fire and Rescue Service|accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2011, while Smith was visiting the submarine [[HMS Astute (S119)]] as part of the tour, a sailor started shooting, and killed an officer. Smith intervened and helped apprehend the sailor. He was awarded the [[George Medal]] for his actions.<ref name=bbc13022096>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hampshire-13022096 |title=Council boss 'disarmed gunman' on nuclear submarine |publisher=BBC News |date=8 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hampshire-20431302 |publisher=BBC News |title=George Medals for men who tackled gunman Ryan Donovan|date=21 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nAs council leader in 2011, Smith initiated an up to 5.5% pay cut on council employees as part of a bid to cut the council's expenditure by \u00a376 million by 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2012/jan/24/southampton-council-strikes-royston-smith|work=The Guardian|title=Unions and Southampton council go head to head over cuts |last=Milmo|first=Dan|accessdate=13 December 2019|date=24 January 2012}}</ref> In response, unions took industrial action by refusing to collect rubbish in the council.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hampshire-13695474|title=Southampton refuse collectors extend strike|publisher=BBC News|date=8 June 2011|accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nSmith stood as a Conservative candidate in the [[Southampton Itchen (UK Parliament constituency)|Southampton Itchen]] constituency in the 2010 general election. He came second in the seat, losing by 192 votes to the incumbent Labour MP [[John Denham (politician)|John Denham]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/election-2010/7691686/General-Election-2010-John-Denham-scrapes-victory-in-Southampton-Itchen-seat.html|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=7 May 2010|accessdate=29 October 2019|title=General Election 2010: John Denham scrapes victory in Southampton Itchen seat|last=Wardrop|first=Murray}}</ref> Smith was elected as MP for the constituency in the subsequent 2015 general election and was re-elected in the 2017 and 2019 general elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://electionresults.parliament.uk/election/2015-05-07/results/Location/Constituency/Southampton,%20Itchen|publisher=parliament.uk|accessdate=29 October 2019|title=Southampton, Itchen - 2015 Election Results}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-eu-election-insight/leave-or-remain-brexit-bind-could-hurt-labour-in-a-snap-election-idUKKCN1VJ1HP|title=Leave or remain? Brexit bind could hurt Labour in a snap election|last=MacLellan|first=Kylie|date=29 August 2019|accessdate=29 October 2019|publisher=Reuters}}</ref> \n\n===House of Commons Select Committee Membership===  \nSmith sat on the [[Work and Pensions Select Committee]] between December 2016 and May 2017. He was a part of the [[Committees on Arms Export Controls]] between October 2017 and July 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/royston-smith/4478|title=Royston Smith MP|publisher=parliament.uk|accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe has been a member of the [[Foreign Affairs Select Committee]] since September 2017.<ref>https://members.parliament.uk/member/4478/career|accessdate=09 March 2020</ref> <ref>https://committees.parliament.uk/committee/78/foreign-affairs-committee/membership/|accessdate=09 March 2020</ref>\n\n===Remunerated outside interests===  \nSmith received regular payments of \u00a36,000 per quarter from landowners Barker Mill Estates <ref>{{cite web|url=https://barkermillestates.com/|title=Home - Barker-Mill Estates|date=29 August 2019|accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref> for most of his career as an MP. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/mps-lords-and-offices/standards-and-financial-interests/parliamentary-commissioner-for-standards/registers-of-interests/register-of-members-financial-interests/|title=Register of Members' Financial Interests|publisher=parliament.uk|accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/721697/CSPL_MPs__outside_interests_-_full_report.PDF|title=MPs' Outside Interests|publisher=Committee on Standards in Public Life|website=gov.uk|date=3 July 2018|accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref> {{Failed verification|date=March 2020}}  \n\n===Brexit===\nSmith supported [[Brexit]] in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 UK EU membership referendum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-35616946|title=EU vote: Where the cabinet and other MPs stand|publisher=BBC News|date=22 June 2016|accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref> He voted for the then Prime Minister [[Theresa May]]'s Brexit withdrawal agreement on 29 March 2019. Smith also voted against any [[Proposed referendum on the Brexit withdrawal agreement|referendum on a withdrawal agreement]] in the indicative votes on 27 March.<ref name=FT>{{cite news|url=https://ig.ft.com/brexit-exit-deal-vote/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902092554/https://ig.ft.com/brexit-exit-deal-vote/|archivedate=2 September 2019|date=29 March 2019|title=How MPs voted on May's withdrawal deal defeat|work=Financial Times}}</ref> He then voted for the Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]]'s Brexit withdrawal agreement in October.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-deal-how-my-mp-voted-labour-conservative-boris-johnson-a9167026.html|work=The Independent|title=How your MP voted for Boris Johnson's Brexit deal|date=23 October 2019|accessdate=29 October 2019|last=Buchan|first=Lizzy}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, he successful secured Government's Brexit contingency funding for Southampton after writing a letter to [[Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government]] [[James Brokenshire]]. He made the case that Brexit-related gridlock caused by disruption at south coast ports could have a major impact on hospitals and other services. Smith believed Southampton needs tens of thousands of pounds to cope with what he describes as \u201cevery eventuality\u201d in the letter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyecho.co.uk/news/17439919.mps-demand-extra-cash-for-hampshire-as-county-prepares-for-potential-no-deal-brexit-chaos/|title=MPs demand extra cash for Hampshire as county prepares for potential no-deal Brexit chaos|website=Daily Echo|language=en|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref>  A few days afterwards, Southampton was awarded \u00a3273,000 to help the port cope with the impact of Brexit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyecho.co.uk/news/17448638.city-handed-273k-to-help-port-cope-with-fallout-from-brexit/|title=City handed \u00a3273k to help port cope with fallout from Brexit|website=Daily Echo|language=en|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref>\n\n=== Campaigning for jobs and investment to Southampton ===\nSmith has been campaigning for a fair deal for Southampton since he was a [[Councillor]]. In 2010, he fought for [[Itchen College]] when the Government withdrew funding, to protect Southampton's estate regeneration programme and get investment into [[Woolston, Southampton|Woolston]] shopping parade.<ref name=\"dailyecho.co.uk\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyecho.co.uk/news/5729452.royston-smith-conservative-southampton-itchen/|title=Royston Smith, Conservative, Southampton Itchen|website=Daily Echo|language=en|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref>\n \t\nIn 2019, writing in ''The Times'', Smith associated Southampton with [[Post-industrial economy|post-industrial]] towns to make the argument that [[Government ministers|Government Ministers]] should look South not just North when it comes to Government priorities in regenerating cities.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/look-south-pm-it-s-not-just-about-helping-labour-leavers-in-the-north-xwwkhvplp|title=Look south PM, it's not just about helping Labour Leavers in the north|last=Smith|first=Royston|date=2019-02-13|access-date=2019-07-26|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nIn the House of Commons Chamber, Smith asked the Government several times what is being done to create jobs with higher pay and better prospects.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2019-03-18/debates/928B4617-5BAC-4620-9F16-E086EBA22479/Employment?highlight=jobs#contribution-EC855A49-459B-4524-8311-650C9D8F1A63)%20(https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2019-04-24/debates/D1A68F81-35D0-4D36-B91C-8FC555CCC3E6/TopicalQuestions?highlight=jobs#contribution-65A1996F-A8D6-488C-8095-A2A47E2C3A76|title=Employment - Hansard|website=hansard.parliament.uk|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref>\n\n=== Campaign to honour the Spitfire ===\nIn 2018, Smith met with the Minister with responsibility for coastal communities to discuss his campaign to honour the [[Supermarine Spitfire|Spitfire]] and how Southampton could put in a bid to help fund a fitting memorial to the iconic aircraft. [[R. J. Mitchell]] designed the Spitfire in Southampton and its first flight was from [[Eastleigh]] Airport.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.roystonsmith.co.uk/campaign-honour-spitfire-continues/|title=Campaign to honour the Spitfire continues|last=Smith|first=Royston|date=2018-03-02|website=Royston Smith - At the heart of Southampton|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March 2017, Smith held a Westminster Hall debate in Parliament calling on the Government to help fund The National Tribute to The [[Royal Air Force]] in Southampton. The debate received support from MPs on all sides of the house.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2017-03-28/debates/6EB2C2FF-A4B2-44C1-B58B-E891E37E18CE/NationalSpitfireProject?highlight=spitfire#contribution-FFD8462D-4A61-4619-AE97-65AF4D311F86|title=National Spitfire Project - Hansard|website=hansard.parliament.uk|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.roystonsmith.co.uk/royston-leads-westminster-hall-debate-spitfire/|title=Royston leads Westminster Hall debate on the Spitfire|last=Smith|first=Royston|date=2017-03-30|website=Royston Smith - At the heart of Southampton|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn 2011, Smith was stopped by police for not wearing a seat belt and later found to have been driving an uninsured car. He was fined and given six points on his driving licence.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hampshire-15864926|title=Uninsured Southampton council leader Royston Smith fined|date=23 November 2011|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=28 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter the 2015 election, [[UK Independence Party|UKIP]] candidate Kim Rose claimed that he had received data on voters in the constituency and advice from Smith to assist his campaign.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/may/31/royston-smith-faces-claims-ukip-helped-ukip-candidate|work=The Guardian|title=Conservative MP faces claims he helped Ukip candidate target Labour voters|last=Perraudin|first=Frances|date=31 May 2015|accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref> Smith denied the allegations. Police have looked into the matter and said Smith had no case to answer. Smith\u2019s local party association, Southampton Itchen Conservative Association was registered with the [[Information Commissioner's Office]], and the [[Chairman of the Conservative Party|Conservative Party Chairman]] at the time, [[Andrew Feldman, Baron Feldman of Elstree|Lord Feldman,]] wrote to complainants to say that no data protection breach had occurred.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyecho.co.uk/news/13931416.southampton-mp-in-clear-over-voter-allegations/|title=Southampton MP in clear over voter allegations|website=Daily Echo|language=en|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 February 2016, Smith was named as Britain's least active MP out of all the MPs that are newly elected in 2015 by 'The Independent'. Smith defended his record by stating that, \"I find Southampton is a challenging constituency. He added, \"Southampton is a challenging constituency and I spend my time doing as much as I can locally. I don't spend hours in the House of Commons waiting to make a three-minute speech.\" \n.<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\">{{cite news|work=The Independent|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tory-mp-royston-smith-is-least-active-among-parliaments-new-members-a6886761.html|title=This is the least active MP of Parliament's new members|date=20 February 2016|accessdate=30 December 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hampshire-35629442|title='Least active MP' defends record|date=22 February 2016|work=BBC News|accessdate=30 December 2017|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> At the same time Smith was found to have received funds for Consultancy work outside of Parliamentary business. {{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nIn December 2017, Smith suggested cyclists should only use roads with cycle lanes on them, stating that cyclists should \"consider when and where they cycle\" in order to \"make the roads safer\". The comments came after a 64-year-old cyclist died after colliding with a lorry on Portsmouth Road, Woolston. He was criticised by campaigners on the grounds that \"we should be encouraging more people to use the roads, not less\", while it was subsequently reported that Smith had recently called for \u00a311.5 million in grant funding for the city's cycling strategy, such as creating new cycle lanes, to be diverted elsewhere.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyecho.co.uk/news/15783263.MP_calls_for_cyclists_to_think_twice_before_using_busy_roads_following_fatal_crash/|title=MP calls for cyclists to think twice before using busy roads following fatal crash|date=20 December 2017|newspaper=Daily Echo|accessdate=9 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/latest-news/mp-says-cyclists-stick-cycle-lanes-rider-dies-crash-lorry-363973|title=MP says cyclists should 'stick to cycle lanes' after rider dies in crash with lorry|date=21 December 2017|newspaper=Cycling Weekly|accessdate=9 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe lives in [[Peartree (ward)|Peartree]], Southampton.<ref name=\"dailyecho.co.uk\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=royston-smith/4478 |publicwhip=Royston_Smith |theywork=royston_smith}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Denham (politician)|John Denham]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br />for [[Southampton Itchen (UK Parliament constituency)|Southampton Itchen]]|years=[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{South East Conservative Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Royston}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Southampton]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the George Medal]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force airmen]]\n[[Category:Leaders of local authorities of England]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eControversies:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Royston_Smith"}
{"title_page": "Paula Sherriff", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Paula Sherriff\n| honorific-suffix = \n| office1 = [[Department for Health|Shadow Minister for Social Care and Mental Health]]\n| leader1 = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start1 = 12 January  2018\n| term_end1 = 6 November 2019\n| office2 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Dewsbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Dewsbury]]\n| term_start2 = 7 May 2015\n| term_end2 = 6 November 2019\n| predecessor2 = [[Simon Reevell]]\n| successor2 = [[Mark Eastwood]]\n| majority2 = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1975|4|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| website = {{url|paulasherriff.org.uk|Official website}}\n| successor1 = To be appointed\n| predecessor1 = Position established\n}}\n'''Paula Michelle Sherriff''' (born 16 April 1975) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician who served as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Dewsbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Dewsbury]] from 2015 to 2019. She won the seat from the [[Conservative Party(UK)|Conservative]]s at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], was re-elected in [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000666|title= Election 2017: Dewsbury Parliamentary constituency|date=9 June 2017|accessdate=9 June 2017|work=[[BBC News]]}}</ref> but was defeated at the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]]. Sherriff was previously a councillor for [[Pontefract North (electoral ward)|Pontefract North]] in [[Pontefract]] on [[Wakefield District Council]].\n\n== Personal life ==\nBefore being elected as a Member of Parliament, Sherriff worked in the [[Police|police force]], providing victim support, and on the frontline of the National Health Service in community care.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paulasherriff.org.uk/about|title=About|website=Paula Sherriff|accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref> Her sister Lee Sherriff was an unsuccessful candidate for [[Carlisle (UK Parliament constituency)|Carlisle]] in the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/may/15/labour-carlisle-stroud-tory-marginals-ed-miliband|title=\u2018Better the devil you know\u2019: two towns that refused to ride with Labour|last=Henley|first=Jon|date=15 May 2015|work=The Guardian|accessdate=29 November 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Sherriff was diagnosed with [[breast cancer]].<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=paulasherriff |author=Paula Sherriff |number=1240952917475102726 |date = 20 March 2020 |title=So, it has now been confirmed that I have breast cancer, following discovery of a lump. My treatment plan will be determined after a few more tests. Yes I\u2019m scared but I\u2019m gonna kick cancer\u2019s a**e! Please, please examine your breasts and see a GP if anything seems unusual x }}</ref>\n\n== Parliamentary career ==\nFollowing her election, in September 2015 Sherriff secured an agreement from [[WHSmith]] to reduce the price of their goods in hospitals, against whom had she had launched a campaign for exploiting vulnerable patients and their families. Subsequently, the company agreed to match their high street prices in hospital stores.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paulasherriff.org.uk/wh_smith_climb|title=Paula secures WH Smith climb down on hospital shop pricing|website=Paula Sherriff|accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Sherriff was appointed as a ministerial aide to shadow local government and communities secretary [[Jon Trickett]]. On 11 January 2016, Sherriff resigned from this role to campaign against \"Tory cuts\" and to focus on her work on the health select committee.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news |title=Labour's Catherine McKinnell quits shadow cabinet|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-35281203 |work =[[BBC News]]|date = 11 January 2016 |accessdate=10 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nPaula Sherriff became the first backbench MP in Parliamentary history to have an amendment to a government Budget resolution successfully adopted when her motion to abolish the \"[[Tampon Tax]]\" was passed. On 21 March 2016, the government acknowledged that the \"[[Tampon Tax]]\" would be abolished.  Both the Prime Minister and the Leader of the Labour Party commended her work on the issue.<ref>{{cite news | last = Simons | first = Ned | title =  MPs back abolition of tampon tax after Government accepts Labour amendment to budget | url = http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/tampon-tax-abolished-by-vote-of-mps_uk_56f1668ae4b0fbd4fe08aae5 | work = [[Huffington Post]] |date = 22 March 2016 |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe supported [[Owen Smith]] in the [[2016 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2016 Labour Party leadership election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/mps-nominating-owen-smith-labour-8451186|title=Which MPs are nominating Owen Smith in the Labour leadership contest?|last1=Smith|first1=Mikey|date=20 July 2016|work=Mirror|accessdate=10 November 2018|last2=Bloom|first2=Dan|location=}}</ref>\n\nSherriff secured a U-turn on planned reduction in bed numbers at Dewsbury hospital and has campaigned against the hospital being downgraded.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thepressnews.co.uk/press-news/-politically-speaking-paula-sherriff-mp-for-dewsbury-and-mirfield-july-28-2017|title=The Press - \u2018Politically speaking\u2019 by Paula Sherriff|website=The Press|accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref> Sherriff has also campaigned against proposed downgrades to [[Huddersfield Royal Infirmary]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/paulasherriff/status/1076466165537521664|title=Proud to join phenomenal campaigners at HRI today. All standing together with a united message that this Government will not take our precious NHS services away! Hands off HRI @MattHancock! @HoHRIltd @HandsOffNHS_org @Thelma_WalkerMPpic.twitter.com/rO9dODx8QS|last=Sherriff|first=Paula|date=22 December 2018|website=@paulasherriff|accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nSherriff is Chair of the All-Party Parliamentary Groups on Hate Crime and Women's\u2019 Health and has secured millions of pounds of funding for endometriosis research.\n\nShe was appointed [[Shadow Minister for Mental Health and Social Care]] in January 2018 and has led on the Labour Party's efforts to secure additional funding for mental health services and provide early intervention with effective child and adolescent mental health services.<ref>{{cite news|title=Paula Sherriff promoted to Labour's front bench|url=http://www.examiner.co.uk/news/west-yorkshire-news/paula-sherriff-promoted-labours-front-14159580|accessdate=16 January 2018|publisher=Huddersfield Examiner|date=12 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, Sherriff took part in the \"humbug debate\" and criticised [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Boris Johnson]] for his inflammatory language.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Belam|first=Martin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/sep/26/surrender-humbug-most-heated-exchanges-in-commons-debate|title='Surrender, humbug': key heated exchanges in Commons debate|date=2019-09-26|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-25|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49833804|title=MPs' fury at PM's 'dangerous language'|date=2019-09-25|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-02-25|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Deacon|first=Michael|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/09/26/shocking-scenes-wednesday-mood-commons-has-turned-utterly-rancid/|title=After those shocking scenes on Wednesday, the mood in the Commons has turned utterly rancid|date=2019-09-26|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2020-02-25|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uk.news.yahoo.com/im-sick-of-it-mp-tears-into-boris-johnson-for-inflammatory-comments-while-m-ps-receive-death-threats-074428108.html|title=\u2018I\u2019m sick of it\u2019: MP tears into Boris Johnson for \u2018inflammatory comments\u2019 while MPs receive death threats|website=uk.news.yahoo.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|40em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.paulasherriff.org.uk/}}\n* {{UK MP links |parliament=paula-sherriff/4426 |publicwhip=Paula_Sherriff |theywork=paula_sherriff}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Simon Reevell]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n|title =[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Dewsbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Dewsbury]]\n|years=[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\u2013[[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]]\n}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mark Eastwood]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n__FORCETOC__\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sherriff, Paula}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Councillors in West Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:People from Dewsbury]]\n[[Category:British feminists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Paula Sherriff\n| honorific-suffix = \n| office1 = [[Department for Health|Shadow Minister for Social Care and Mental Health]]\n| leader1 = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start1 = 12 January  2018\n| term_end1 = 6 November 2019\n| office2 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Dewsbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Dewsbury]]\n| term_start2 = 7 May 2015\n| term_end2 = 6 November 2019\n| predecessor2 = [[Simon Reevell]]\n| successor2 = [[Mark Eastwood]]\n| majority2 = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1975|4|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| website = {{url|paulasherriff.org.uk|Official website}}\n| successor1 = To be appointed\n| predecessor1 = Position established\n}}\n'''Paula Michelle Sherriff''' (born 16 April 1975) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician who served as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Dewsbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Dewsbury]] from 2015 to 2019. She won the seat from the [[Conservative Party(UK)|Conservative]]s at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], was re-elected in [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000666|title= Election 2017: Dewsbury Parliamentary constituency|date=9 June 2017|accessdate=9 June 2017|work=[[BBC News]]}}</ref> but was defeated at the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]]. Sherriff was previously a councillor for [[Pontefract North (electoral ward)|Pontefract North]] in [[Pontefract]] on [[Wakefield District Council]].\n\n== Personal life ==\nBefore being elected as a Member of Parliament, Sherriff worked in the [[Police|police force]], providing victim support, and on the frontline of the National Health Service in community care.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paulasherriff.org.uk/about|title=About|website=Paula Sherriff|accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref> Her sister Lee Sherriff was an unsuccessful candidate for [[Carlisle (UK Parliament constituency)|Carlisle]] in the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/may/15/labour-carlisle-stroud-tory-marginals-ed-miliband|title=\u2018Better the devil you know\u2019: two towns that refused to ride with Labour|last=Henley|first=Jon|date=15 May 2015|work=The Guardian|accessdate=29 November 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Sherriff was diagnosed with [[breast cancer]].<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=paulasherriff |author=Paula Sherriff |number=1240952917475102726 |date = 20 March 2020 |title=So, it has now been confirmed that I have breast cancer, following discovery of a lump. My treatment plan will be determined after a few more tests. Yes I\u2019m scared but I\u2019m gonna kick cancer\u2019s a**e! Please, please examine your breasts and see a GP if anything seems unusual x }}</ref>\n\n== Parliamentary career ==\nFollowing her election, in September 2015 Sherriff secured an agreement from [[WHSmith]] to reduce the price of their goods in hospitals, against whom had she had launched a campaign for exploiting vulnerable patients and their families. Subsequently, the company agreed to match their high street prices in hospital stores.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paulasherriff.org.uk/wh_smith_climb|title=Paula secures WH Smith climb down on hospital shop pricing|website=Paula Sherriff|accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Sherriff was appointed as a ministerial aide to shadow local government and communities secretary [[Jon Trickett]]. On 11 January 2016, Sherriff resigned from this role to campaign against \"Tory cuts\" and to focus on her work on the health select committee.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news |title=Labour's Catherine McKinnell quits shadow cabinet|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-35281203 |work =[[BBC News]]|date = 11 January 2016 |accessdate=10 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nPaula Sherriff became the first backbench MP in Parliamentary history to have an amendment to a government Budget resolution successfully adopted when her motion to abolish the \"[[Tampon Tax]]\" was passed. On 21 March 2016, the government acknowledged that the \"[[Tampon Tax]]\" would be abolished.  Both the Prime Minister and the Leader of the Labour Party commended her work on the issue.<ref>{{cite news | last = Simons | first = Ned | title =  MPs back abolition of tampon tax after Government accepts Labour amendment to budget | url = http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/tampon-tax-abolished-by-vote-of-mps_uk_56f1668ae4b0fbd4fe08aae5 | work = [[Huffington Post]] |date = 22 March 2016 |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe supported [[Owen Smith]] in the [[2016 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2016 Labour Party leadership election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/mps-nominating-owen-smith-labour-8451186|title=Which MPs are nominating Owen Smith in the Labour leadership contest?|last1=Smith|first1=Mikey|date=20 July 2016|work=Mirror|accessdate=10 November 2018|last2=Bloom|first2=Dan|location=}}</ref>\n\nSherriff secured a U-turn on planned reduction in bed numbers at Dewsbury hospital and has campaigned against the hospital being downgraded.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thepressnews.co.uk/press-news/-politically-speaking-paula-sherriff-mp-for-dewsbury-and-mirfield-july-28-2017|title=The Press - \u2018Politically speaking\u2019 by Paula Sherriff|website=The Press|accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref> Sherriff has also campaigned against proposed downgrades to [[Huddersfield Royal Infirmary]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/paulasherriff/status/1076466165537521664|title=Proud to join phenomenal campaigners at HRI today. All standing together with a united message that this Government will not take our precious NHS services away! Hands off HRI @MattHancock! @HoHRIltd @HandsOffNHS_org @Thelma_WalkerMPpic.twitter.com/rO9dODx8QS|last=Sherriff|first=Paula|date=22 December 2018|website=@paulasherriff|accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nSherriff is Chair of the All-Party Parliamentary Groups on Hate Crime and Women\u2019s\u2019 Health and has secured millions of pounds of funding for endometriosis research.\n\nShe was appointed [[Shadow Minister for Mental Health and Social Care]] in January 2018 and has led on the Labour Party's efforts to secure additional funding for mental health services and provide early intervention with effective child and adolescent mental health services.<ref>{{cite news|title=Paula Sherriff promoted to Labour's front bench|url=http://www.examiner.co.uk/news/west-yorkshire-news/paula-sherriff-promoted-labours-front-14159580|accessdate=16 January 2018|publisher=Huddersfield Examiner|date=12 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, Sherriff took part in the \"humbug debate\" and criticised [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Boris Johnson]] for his inflammatory language.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Belam|first=Martin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/sep/26/surrender-humbug-most-heated-exchanges-in-commons-debate|title='Surrender, humbug': key heated exchanges in Commons debate|date=2019-09-26|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-25|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49833804|title=MPs' fury at PM's 'dangerous language'|date=2019-09-25|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-02-25|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Deacon|first=Michael|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/09/26/shocking-scenes-wednesday-mood-commons-has-turned-utterly-rancid/|title=After those shocking scenes on Wednesday, the mood in the Commons has turned utterly rancid|date=2019-09-26|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2020-02-25|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uk.news.yahoo.com/im-sick-of-it-mp-tears-into-boris-johnson-for-inflammatory-comments-while-m-ps-receive-death-threats-074428108.html|title=\u2018I\u2019m sick of it\u2019: MP tears into Boris Johnson for \u2018inflammatory comments\u2019 while MPs receive death threats|website=uk.news.yahoo.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|40em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.paulasherriff.org.uk/}}\n* {{UK MP links |parliament=paula-sherriff/4426 |publicwhip=Paula_Sherriff |theywork=paula_sherriff}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Simon Reevell]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n|title =[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Dewsbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Dewsbury]]\n|years=[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\u2013[[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]]\n}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mark Eastwood]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n__FORCETOC__\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sherriff, Paula}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Councillors in West Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:People from Dewsbury]]\n[[Category:British feminists]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eParliamentary career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paula_Sherriff"}
